<HEADLINE> U.S. President May Defer Visit to India: PTI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- United States President Bill
Clinton may defer his visit to India with New Delhi unwilling to
accept Washington's demand to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty (CTBT) immediately and unconditionally, the Press Trust of
India (PTI) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that India's position on the CTBT was outlined
by Brajesh Mishra, Indian Prime Minister's principal secretary,
who stated categorically that his country was not close to signing
the treaty.
</P>
<P>
It quoted informed sources as saying that Clinton's visit,
which was put on hold soon after India's nuclear tests last May,
was unlikely to come through this year.
</P>
<P>
Indian prime minister's special envoy Jaswant Singh and U.S.
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott met for several times
since May, most recently last Thursday in New York, but failed to
make any breakthrough in relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
India is keen to realize Clinton's tour of South Asia before
the end of this year while the U.S. has linked the president's
visit to progress made at the ongoing talks with both India and
Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
