<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly Half of Russians Have No Money to Cope With Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Forty-nine percent of Russia's
urban residents have no money to soften the impact of the
financial crisis, according to a recent poll earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen percent of the respondents were buying extra supplies
of foodstuffs, 5 percent were stocking up on consumer goods, 4
percent were buying durables and another 4 percent were buying
U.S. dollars, the poll shows.
</P>
<P>
The poll was organized by the All-Russia Public Opinion Center
and involved 1,862 Russian residents in September.
</P>
<P>
Eight percent of those polled declined to say what they were
doing to ease the impact of the crisis, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Only 3 percent of those surveyed think the actual situation is
better than what it is believed to be. They said they were doing
nothing at all to cope with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
For two weeks prices have been escalating rapidly while the
ruble nosedives, and the country continues to go without a fully
functioning government.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, the present legal monthly minimum wage, 83.49 rubles
(about 5 U.S. dollars), can only buy one liter of vegetable oil,
two cans of meat preserves and one loaf of bread.
</P>
<P>
As of Monday, prices for some imported foodstuffs on wholesale
markets in the capital city were up 100-500 percent against the
pre-crisis levels, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Prices for most Russian-produced food products, including
sausage, butter, canned meat, pasta and oil, jumped 50-100 percent
on the average.
</P>
<P>
Goods with long shelf life are vanishing from Moscow's stores,
which are crowded with people eager to stockpile food.
</P>
<P>
However, prices of domestically produced bread and milk haven't
changed much, a relief for many pensioners who can now barely
survive on these staples. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
