<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Says Cooperation With Turkey Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said here Monday that the Israeli-Turkish
cooperation would improve the prosperity and security of the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting with his Turkish
counterpart Mesut Yilmaz, Netanyahu said that he discussed with
Yilmaz the economic, political and defense relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed that Israeli cooperation with Turkey was the
"natural cooperation" that is "not against anyone" and will
contribute to the stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
He tried to allay the growing suspicion and anger among the
Arab and Islamic world towards Israel's booming military
cooperation, saying the Israeli-Turkish cooperation would do no
harm to Syria, which has disputes with both Israel and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He urged Syrians to resume the negotiations with Israel which
have been stalled since early 1996 after making marked progress in
talks held between Syria and Israel's previous Labor government.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Yilmaz said that his visit was aimed at improving
the stability and security of the region. He believed that the
whole region would benefit from the better relations between
Turkey and Israel.
</P>
<P>
He counterattacked those who protested against the booming
Israeli-Turkish cooperation, saying that the real sources of
instability in the Middle East should be "among those who have
aggressive policies."
</P>
<P>
Israel and Turkey began their military cooperation since early
1996 when they signed a military cooperation deal, which allows
Israeli fighter pilots to fly training flights in Turkish air
space. Israel has also been upgrading Turkish fighter planes with
its advanced electronic aviation technologies.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Netanyahu and Yilmaz also discussed ways
to expand the free trade between the two countries. And the two
sides signed an agreement on the agriculture cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, Netanyahu
said he phoned Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Monday morning,
and hoped that Mubarak would help to advance the stalled
negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz also expressed concern over the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations, and said that Turkey would continue to play a
constructive role in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish prime minister arrived here from Jordan Monday
morning for a two-day visit to Israel. He is also to hold talks
with Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's growing military ties with Jordan and Israel have
provoked fears in the Arab and Islamic world about the creation of
a new military axis in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Syria fears military cooperation among its three rivaling
neighbors will leave it encircled by an enemy coalition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
