<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Joint Efforts in Globalization  (Embargoed for Tuesday) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Defined in geographic
terms, little is new about globalization because interconnected
human activity on a worldwide scale has existed for centuries. But
"the form of contemporary globalization is new."
</P>
<P>
The comparative statement came as U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Tuesday presented his annual report to the 52nd session
of the General Assembly, which is scheduled to end on the same day
before adopting this work report.
</P>
<P>
The concept of globalization covers the environmental and
economic dimensions, Annan said in his 32-page report in English,
citing three new characteristics of the globalization.
</P>
<P>
First, "demographic momentum, together with patterns of land
use and energy consumption, has always affected local and
subregional ecosystems," he said.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, "today these and other human factors increasingly
affect the planet's ecology as a whole, be it through ozone
depletion, global warming or diminishing biodiversity," he said.
</P>
<P>
The last but not least, "the technological advances and open
borders that enable the commercial firms to organize the
production of goods and services transnationally also enable
terrorist networks, criminal syndicates, drug traffickers and
money launderers to project their reach across the globe," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"These new dimensions of globalization can only be addressed
multilaterally, by the United Nations and by other international
institutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the environmental dimension, Annan said that international
cooperation has a vital role to play in arresting and reversing
the potentially harmful effects of human activities on the
environment.
</P>
<P>
In June 1997, the General Assembly considered a study warning
that, without preventive measure, two thirds of the world's
population could face freshwater scarcity and water quality
problems by 2005. In 1998, a series of international meetings
sought to identify approaching policy responses.
</P>
<P>
On the economic dimension, Annan said that "in cooperation with
other multilateral organizations, the United Nations has sought to
strengthen normative, legal and institutional frameworks that will
allow the global economy to operate more effectively and
equitably."
</P>
<P>
During the past year, the Asian financial crisis has
intensified and now affects countries on every continent. "It has
exacted steep and possibly long-lasting social costs in East Asia,
and raised serious concerns about the operations of unregulated
financial markets," he said.
</P>
<P>
Looking beyond the immediate crisis, the U.N. Economic and
Social Council devoted its 1988 high-level segment to market
access in the context of globalization, and debated how
developments since the Uruguay Round are affecting developing and
least developing countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
In September 1988, the General Assembly will, for the first
time, hold a high-level dialogue on the social and economic impact
of globalization and interdependence and their policy
implications, Annan added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on International Peace, Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The world has been
mercifully free from large-scale regional conflict over the past
year, but many local wars have continued with new ones breaking
out, said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In his annual report 1998 on peace and Security, Annan said
there had been some important successes for the international
community, including the restoration of the democratically elected
Government in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the world lived through a period of high tension in
February when Iraq seemed set on refusing to comply with its
disarmament obligations, and some Member States prepared for
military action to enforce compliance. War was averted by the
timely collective action of the international community.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, peace in many parts of the world
remains precarious, and of particular concern is the lack of
progress in the Middle East peace process, the turmoil in
Afghanistan, the escalation of violence in Kosovo, the ongoing
civil war in the Sudan, the continuing instability and violence in
the Democratic Republic of the Congo and the rest of the Great
Lakes region, and the return to civil war in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Nor is the human race yet delivered from the threat of unclear
annihilation, said the U.N. chief, adding the successes of
previous year, the indefinite extension of the Treaty on the
Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons and the signing of the
Comprehensive Nuclear-Tear-Ban Treaty, had been called into
question this year by the decisions of India and Pakistan to
conduct underground nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the adoption, late in 1997, of the Ottawa Convention
on the Prohibition of the Use, Stockpiling, production and
Transfer of Anti-Personnel Mines and on Their Destruction was an
unprecedented achievement, and similarly, the adoption of the
Statute of the International Criminal Court at Rome in July was a
historical development in the age-long struggle to punish and
deter war crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on Positive Developments in Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Positive developments
have been made in the area of disarmament for the past year, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In his annual report 1998 on disarmament, Annan said the United
Nations placed disarmament near the center of its mission of peace
and development by reestablishing the Department for Disarmament
Affairs with an Under-Secretary-General as its head.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary-General said the Department played a
critical role in post-conflict peace-building, notably in the
collection, disposal and destruction of weapons and in the
reintegration of former combatants into civil society.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the positive developments include the issuance of
the eight-nation joint declaration on creating a
unclear-weapon-free world, and the establishment of two ad hoc
committees in the Conference on Disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in the past year efforts were also made to
consolidate existing nuclear-weapon-free-zones, notably those in
Africa and in South-East Asia and the move towards the
establishment of another such zone in Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said in the struggle for sustainable peace and
development, steps need to be taken to curb the flow of small arms
circulating in civil society, and one approach to this problem
would be to seek to build a global consensus on monitoring and
controlling illicit arms transfers and their links with
trafficking in other contraband goods.
</P>
<P>
Annan called on the Member States to increase and improve their
participation in the United Nations Register of Conventional Arms
and the system for standardized reporting of military expenditures
so as to achieve greater openness and transparency in military
matters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Faction Leaders Believe in Govt on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Faction leaders in central
Somalia ended up a peace conference Monday, with the belief that
a lasting peace and a broad-based government for Somalia could
only be achieved through grassroots peace negotiations among all
the Somalis in general.
</P>
<P>
The peace promoting conference attended by hundreds of
intellectuals, traditional leaders as well as politicians from
the districts of the central region of Hiran was concluded Monday
in the town of Beletuein, 300 Km North of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman of the conference, the meeting
which lasted for four days was aimed at opening a peace making
dialogue for what is called the Great Hawiye communities in
Beletuein within four weeks beginning from Monday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Ibrahim Habeb Nur from the Hiran region
dominant clan of Hawadle, said the conference has also sent
official invitation letters to all the Hawiye leaders.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which was chaired by Colonel Omar Hashi Aden,
is reportedly initiated by the Ugas of the Hawadle clan, Ugas
Khalif Ugas Robleh in an effort of pacifying the Hawiye
communities, including the Hawadle clan who fought politically
and clan-wise in the past seven year.
</P>
<P>
The call by the politicians of Hiran region coincides with
other political settlement tentative by the recently arrived
governor of Mogadishu, Hussein Ali Ahmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on UN Peace-keeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The international
community had began to overcome its reluctance to make use of the
U.N. peace-keeping capacity in the past year, Annan said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his annual report 1998 on peace-keeping, Annan said the
Security Council authorized two new peacekeeping operations, the
United Nations Mission in the Central African Republic and the
United Nations Observer Mission in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said at the U.N. Headquarters, the
Department of Peacekeeping Operations continued its efforts
to strengthen the Organization's capacity to respond swiftly.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the past year had seen some progress in the
development of the United Nations standby arrangements system,
which now includes 74 Member States, with over 100,000 personnel
pledged in the framework of the system.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said the total number of peacekeepers in the
field had declined since the early 1990s, as a consequence of the
winding down of several major United Nations operations, but the
actual number of United Nations peacekeepers operations had in
fact risen from 15 to 17 in the past year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
