<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Again Rejects Chernomyrdin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma once
again rejected Viktor Chernomyrdin's nomination as prime minister
in the second voting on Monday, despite earlier efforts to break
the political stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Only 138 deputies at the lower house of parliament voted for
Chernomyrdin, who was renamed premier August 24 after five months
in the political wilderness, way below the required simple
majority of 226 votes. Two hundred and seventy-three deputies
voted against with one abstention.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear when the third, or final, vote will take
place. Under the Russian constitution, if the nomination is
rejected three times, the president will have to dissolve the Duma
and call new elections within three months.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, President Boris Yeltsin chaired a roundtable
meeting participated by Chernomyrdin, speakers of both houses of
parliament and leaders of major political factions.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, which was designed to end the impasse over the
government crisis, Yeltsin signed a "unprecedented document" that
is expected to give the State Duma more power in state affairs,
Yeltsin's spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
But Communists and their allies in the Duma insisted that they
would vote against Chernomyrdin again.
</P>
<P>
"Our stance remains unchanged," Communist leader Gennady
Zyuganov said after the roundtable meeting. "He (Chernomyrdin)
doesn't even understand the program he has proposed."
</P>
<P>
Born on April 9, 1938, in Orenburg District, Chernomyrdin was
graduated from Kuybyshev Polytechnic School. Once an operator in
the oil refinery industry and a soldier in the Soviet army, he
became minister of gas in 1985 and stayed on the position until
the disintegration of the Soviet Union in 1989
</P>
<P>
He served as chairman of council of ministers (later called
prime minister) from December 1992 to March 1998 before being
sacked by President Yeltsin in a sudden government reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Five months later, Yeltsin fired Chernomyrdin's successor and
appointed Chernomyrdin as acting prime minister on August 23 when
Russia was hit by a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been without a full functioning government for the
past two weeks. The political crisis has made the economic crisis
even worse.
</P>
<P>
The ruble has shed more than 200 percent against the
U.S. dollar in three weeks, forcing up prices and inflation.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, the present monthly minimum wage set by law, at
83.49 rubles (about five U.S. dollars), can only buy one liter of
vegetable oil, two cans of meat preserves and one loaf of bread.
</P>
<P>
As of Monday, prices for some imported foodstuffs on wholesale
markets in the capital city were up 100-500 percent against the
pre-crisis levels, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Prices for most Russian-produced food products, including
sausages, butter, canned meat, pasta and oil, jumped 50-100
percent on average.
</P>
<P>
Goods with long shelf life are vanishing from Moscow's stores,
which are crowded with people eager to stockpile food in
anticipation of further fall of the ruble and more price hikes.
</P>
<P>
However, prices for domestically produced bread and milk
haven't changed much, a relief for many pensioners who can now
barely survive on these staples.
</P>
<P>
According to a poll taken last week, 49 percent of Russia's
urban residents have no money to soften the impact of the
financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi King Urges Iran, Taliban to Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabian King Fahd
Bin Abdelaziz Monday urged Iran and Afghan Taliban militia to
exercise restraint and resolve their disputes peacefully, the
Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) reported from Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd issued his call at the Cabinet session he chaired for
the first time after recuperation from his recent illness.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran and Taliban should start "a constructive
dialogue that embodies the spirit of Islamic brotherhood and
sincere intents..."
</P>
<P>
Fahd's statement came amid rising tension between Iran and
Taliban after Tehran accused the Taliban militia of kidnapping
10 Iranian diplomats when they took over the northern city of
Mazari Sharif on August 8.
</P>
<P>
Since the Taliban regime is only recognized by Saudi Arabia,
the United Arab Emirates and Pakistan, the Iranian government has
recently asked Pakistan and Saudi Arabia for their help in
securing the release of the diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Tehran has also sought help from the United Nations in rescuing
the Iranian diplomats and dozens of Iranian citizens allegedly
held by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
So far the Taliban has denied holding the Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
To flex its military muscle, Iran has recently held a massive
military exercise near the border with Afghanistan and deployed
some 70,000 troops along the border to build up pressure on the
Taliban.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz paid an
one-day visit to Saudi Arabia, where he consulted with senior
Saudi officials on the Iranian-Taliban crisis.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has not officially stated whether it will play any
mediation role. But Kuna reported that Riyadh has promised to help
defuse the tension in coordination with Pakistan so to spare the
bloodshed of the Muslims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0023 </DOCNO>
