<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Congress, Ruling BJP Lash Out at Each Other </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The opposition Congress
party leader Sonia Gandhi Monday charged the India government led
by the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) with misrule while the BJP
said the Congress party's latest session was a total failure.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a convention of Congress workers in Bhopal, capital
of central Madhya Pradesh, Sonia Gandhi lamented the price rise
of essential commodities and growing anarchy under the BJP, saying
there was no one to take care of the poor.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) quoted the Congress leader as
saying that the people already groaning under spiraling prices
were now living under the constant fear of consuming adulterated
foodstuff.
</P>
<P>
A hundred people have died of dropsy, caused mainly by
adulterated oil, in the past three weeks in many areas of the
country, including the Indian capital.
</P>
<P>
Despite such grave provocation of people's miseries, she said,
her party had acted with restraint and not tried to manipulate the
situation to topple the BJP-led government.
</P>
<P>
But as a responsible opposition, she reiterated, the Congress
was ready to shoulder the responsibility of governing at the
center should the government under Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee collapse because of its inherent weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
In a significant policy change, the Congress decided Sunday to
keep its option open to lead a coalition government instead of
forming an alternative administration on its own.
</P>
<P>
A BJP spokesman said Monday that the three-day brainstorming
session of the Congress party which ended Sunday was a total
failure and it showed the party lacked cohesion and was confused
on ideology.
</P>
<P>
Krishan Lal Sharma said here Monday that previous governments
led by the Congress had failed to provide stability ever after
former prime minister Rajiv Gandhi had secured an overwhelming
majority in 1984 in Lok Sabha, the lower house of Indian
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Sonia Gandhi's remarks that the Congress would
stake claim in case the BJP-led government falls, Sharma said the
government would stay and the opposition would not succeed in its
moves to destabilize it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
