<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Rice Conference Convened to Boost Rice Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Rice
Commission (IRC) convened here Monday to mainly explore ways to
meet the challenges to sustainable rice production.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session of the IRC, which is under the Food and
Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), FAO's
Director-General Jacques Diouf said the three-day meeting was held
at a time when 800 million people around the world are still
suffering mal-nutrition and the demand for rice is on rise.
</P>
<P>
Diouf said the immediate task for the 61 IRC member states,
world major rice producers, is to identify ways of raising
production while conserving the natural resource bases for future
generation.
</P>
<P>
Most of consumers who depend on rice as their primary food
intake live in the developing countries where farm holdings are
small and most of the farmers are poor and have limited resources,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Diouf also stressed the need to develop "rice and rice-based
production systems that fit in to socio-economic environments,
especially where the participation of women is dominant, and which
are capable of reducting risks of rural poverty."
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Diouf said "since 1990, the growth rate of rice
production in many countries, especially in Asia, has been lower
than the growth rate of population."
</P>
<P>
Diouf ascribed the disparity partly to the expansion of
industrialization and urbanization that has been increasingly in
competition with land and water resources for rice production.
</P>
<P>
On the other, intensive cultivation in irrigated areas has led
to yield decline and negative impacts on the environment, losses
of natural resources and biodiversity, and social inequity, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
FAO estimated world paddy rice production hit record 572
million tonnes in 1997, up 2 million from 1996, while world rice
trade volume in 1997 dropped to 18.4 million tonnes, 1.2 million
tonnes lower than that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The IRC was set up at the Fourth FAO Conference in 1948 against
the backdrop of an imminent worldwide food shortage to promote
cooperation in member countries in rice production, conservation,
distribution and consumption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Improves Security Through Education of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Security in Uganda has been
improved mainly by way of educating police force and the general
public, a security education report said.
</P>
<P>
The report entitled "Security Education to the Public About Bomb
Threats" is being implemented now throughout the country, Central
Region Police Commander Bakesiima Chrisostom told Xinhua Monday.
</P>
<P>
The police officers are now being trained to know more about
bombs and measures to be taken in emergencies. Only when
policemen learn more about it can they handle the matter
effectively, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
Terrorism is an international phenomenon which has been
increasingly affecting all the people in Uganda. Physical
security measures alone cannot exhaustively and effectively fight
terrorism, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The fight against terrorism is a social responsibility through
collective effort to eradicate this problem. The report requests
the general public to report to the police if anything suspicious
is discovered.
</P>
<P>
It also gives tips to people on what packages are suspicious
and what should be done when one is under bomb threats or after a
bomb goes off.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the education, most people now are more
enlightened and more alert and the capital remains relatively
quiet these days after disastrous bus bomb blasts last month.
</P>
<P>
Kampala Region Police Commander Benjamin Namanya told Xinhua
that some suspects allegedly involved in the bus blasts have been
sent to court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
