<HEADLINE> Romania: Small, Medium-Sized Companies in Great Difficulty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 7 (Xinhua) -- President of Romania's
Chamber of Commerce and Industry George Cojocaru is for "milder
taxation", in order not to burden very much the small and
medium-sized companies, as it happens today.
</P>
<P>
"More than 90 percent of the 567,949 companies registered in
Romania's Chamber of Commerce and Industry are small and
medium-sized units and they face at present the most difficult
state since 1990," the local daily Curentul Monday citing Cojocaru
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thirty percent of the newly created small and medium-sized units
are on the verge of bankrupcy, about a year after birth, Cojocaru
said, adding that about half of them find it difficult to survive.
Only 20 percent of them make profit, he said.
</P>
<P>
An X-ray of the structure of the small and medium-sized
companies showed that about 92 percent of them have less than 9
employees. Only 0.7 percent of the small and medium-sized
enterprises belong to the category of big companies, numbering
more than 250 employees.
</P>
<P>
Many of the 380,000 companies having forwarded the balance
sheet had zero turnover in 1997. Around 227,000 companies scored a
net profit and 110,000 net losses, the total losses amounting to
28,447 billion lei(3.16 billion U.S. dollars), 8,317 billion lei
(924 million U.S. dollars) more than the total profit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
