<HEADLINE> Zambia's Reserves Drop to Less Than $100M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's foreign exchange
reserves stood at an all-time low of less than 100 million U.S.
Dollars in July.
</P>
<P>
The latest edition of Zambia's Macro-economic Indicators
obtained from the ministry of finance Monday shows that the gross
official reserves had fallen to 99.02 million from 117.618
million Dollars in June.
</P>
<P>
An official at the ministry said on anonymity that Zambia's
reserves at the moment had reached the lowest, with only about
three weeks worth of import cover.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the low level of reserves to the government's
heavy debt-servicing, saying that it had been using the little
reserves for clearing the county's huge debt which now stands at
n 7.2 billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has managed to pay out 83 million Dollars towards
debt-servicing from January 1 to the end of last July, despite
not receiving any inflows from the donors in the past months.
</P>
<P>
However, Felix Kani, director of economics at the Bank of
Zambia, said the situation was not bad while maintaining that
there was at least enough reserves for an emergency.
</P>
<P>
Kani advised that the immediate way out of the current strain
on the reserves was to persuade the donors to release their 530
million Dollars of aid pledged in last May at a Paris
Consultative meeting with the Zambian government.
</P>
<P>
The donors insisted that their pledged aid can not be released
until Zambia meets their preconditions such as good governance
and rapid privatization of its cash-trapped copper mines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
