<HEADLINE> Romania: Senior Ruling Party Against Hungarian-Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 7 (Xinhua) -- President of the senior
ruling party Ion Diaconescu believes that negotiations in the
majority coalition can lead to the best solution to the problems
of tuition in the minorities' mother tongues.
</P>
<P>
The leader of Christian Democratic National Peasant Party Ion
Diaconescu, also the Speaker of the Lower Chamber, Monday told a
press conference that "a multicultural university fully satisfies
anybody's needs of mother-tongue tuition, at all grades and
disciplines, without taking the aspect of segregation on ethnic
criteria."
</P>
<P>
The co-ruling Hungarian Democratic Union of Romania (UDMR) last
Saturday threatened to step down from the government unless a
Hungarian-language state university was established in Romania.
</P>
<P>
Ion Diaconescu underscored that a multicultural university was
"the maximal solution to be put before Parliament," and was of the
opinion that if the junior ruling UDMR quit the coalition, "the
solution will be still more difficult to find."
</P>
<P>
According to Diaconescu, the UDMR's presence in the current
ruling coalition is beneficial to both the Hungarian minority and
Romania.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarians of Romania started to ask for a
Hungarian-speaking state university after the fall of Ceausescu in
1989. According to the last census, out of 23 million citizens of
Romania, 1.6 million-strong are Hungarians. They claims to
be entitled to "have got a Hungarian-language university of its
own."
</P>
<P>
The Commission for Education within the Lower Chamber last
Wednesday rejected the idea of founding a state university in the
language of the minorities, deciding that there may be organized
groups and sections in the language of the minorities only within
the multicultural universities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
