Unions (ZCTU) Monday implored the government to honor its
agreement with Coca-Cola Company to reduce excise duty on the
company's soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Zambia News Agency, ZCTU vice-president
Austin Liato said that it was morally wrong for the government to
break its promise after the two parties had agreed on the deal.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement concluded with Coca-Cola three months ago,
the Zambian government pledged to reduce the company's excise
duty while Coca-Cola would invest 75 million U.S. Dollars in the
country.
</P>
<P>
However, the Zambian government failed to honor its pledge and
has referred the reduction of excise duty back to Zambia Revenue
Authority.
</P>
<P>
In a response to this move, Coca-Cola has declared to suspend
its plans to undertake the investment program and to scale down
its operations in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The company also said that the reluctance of the Zambian
government would facilitate its departure from the country.
</P>
<P>
Liato said that if the government would not honor its pledge,
there would be 15,000 people to lose their jobs. 
</P>
