<HEADLINE> EU Watchful Over Renewed Maltese Membership Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
on Monday that it was expecting Malta's new government to
re-submit its bid for a European Union membership.
</P>
<P>
But the commission declined to say whether the island nation
would be admitted to join the front-runners in their pursuit for
EU membership.
</P>
<P>
A spokesperson for European External Relations Commissioner
Hans van den Broek told the press that the union would not be
surprised to receive a renewed application for membership from
Malta in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
She added that the European Commission, the executive body of
the 15-nation European Union and the member states of the union
would review its 1993 assessment that had rated Malta as
politically and economically suitable for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the review will be to see whether the
assessment still holds, the spokesperson added.
</P>
<P>
The last Maltese government freezed the country's membership
application process in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Upon election, Maltese Prime Minister Eddie Fenech Adami said
that a priority of the new government would be to reactivate the
country's application for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
Malta first applied for EU membership in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The European Union started in March this year accession talks
with Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Slovenia, Estonia and
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania and Bulgaria are also
applying for EU membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
