<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Educate One Million Illiterates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique is to wipe out
illiteracy among one million people by 2002.
</P>
<P>
The illiterates will be educated in local languages and
Portuguese, said a report released by the National Bureau of
Basic Education here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Text books in local languages like Sena, Tsonga, Emakua and
Ndau have been proven satisfying in some regions, Mozambican News
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The illiteracy rate, which was 93 percent nationwide in 1975
when the country won its independence, has dropped to 72.8
percent after 1980, when the country carried out the first
illiteracy elimination drive. 
