<HEADLINE> Duma's Left Wing Ready for Dissolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Duma's left-wing opposition
is ready to the dissolution of the lower house of parliament if
the president again nominates Viktor Chernomyrdin for prime
minister for the first time, the Itar-Tass news agency reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
This remark was voiced by head of the Agrarian faction Nikolai
Kharitonov after the State Duma failed again to confirm
Chernomyrdin's nomination in the second vote on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the Duma's left-wing opposition will be
able to collect enough votes against Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Duma's impeachment commission has
prepared a draft resolution on one of the charges brought against
the president and will submit it to the house on Tuesday, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
According to Duma Security Committee chairman Viktor Ilyukhin,
the draft is ready to be put to vote as a basis for further
action.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was once again turned down by the deputies of the
State Duma in its second round of vote on Monday with 138 voting
for and 273 against. There was only one abstention, and 38
deputies did not vote.
</P>
<P>
He received 44 more votes in his favor than on the firs| vote
on him on August 31, when the ballot printouts showed that he won
only 94 votes for, while 251 voting against.
</P>
<P>
The Liberal Democratic Party of Russia faction in the second
vote on Chernomyrdin changed its position. Of the 50 LDPR deputies
48 voted in favor of Chernomyrdin's nomination. In the first vote
on the nominee the entire LDPR faction denied support to
Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
The Our Home is Russia faction granted Chernomyrdin 64 votes
with two deputies not voting.
</P>
<P>
All 43 members of the Yabloko faction unanimously voted against
Chernomyrdin, except one did not participate in the ballot.
</P>
<P>
As the first round of vote the whole Communist Party of Russian
faction voted against the president's premier-nominee. Only two
Communists deputies did not cast votes.
</P>
<P>
The number of Chernomyrdin's supporters in the Russian Regions
group shrank almost by half. Fourteen members of the group voted
in favor of Chernomyrdin's appointment Monday, against 24 on
August 31.
</P>
<P>
After the second failure to confirm Chernomyrdin's nomination
in the State Duma the Russian president did not renominate him.
</P>
<P>
If the State Duma three times failed to endorse the president's
nominee for prime minister, the president has the right to
dissolve the parliament, or have another new candidate for the
post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
