<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Approves Fighters' Sale to Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Despite pleas from Eritrea,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has allowed to sell
upgraded MiG-21 fighter jets to the Ethiopian air forces, Israel
Radio reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The deal had been in limbo since Eritrea protested to Israel,
asking it not to allow the war planes to be sold to Ethiopia on
the ground that Ethiopia and Eritrea were at war.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia had been urgently seeking fighter jets. Israeli Elbit
Systems Company offered to sell 10 MiG-21 jets to it. But the deal
needed to be approved by the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Netanyahu's spokesman Aviv Bushinsky as
saying that the prime minister has decided not to block the deal.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that the deal would not be implemented
immediately and that conflict between the two East African states
would likely ebb before the jets were delivered.
</P>
<P>
"The first airplane is scheduled for delivery within one
year," according to a statement Bushinsky issued. "We hope that
by then the situation will calm down. Israel's official policy is
not to sell arms to areas of conflict," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Elbit is currently upgrading 100 Romanian MiG-21 jets in a
joint venture established with a Romanian company.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia currently has about 70 Soviet-made MiG-21 fighters,
but they are in questionable shape because Ethiopia has not been
able to maintain them properly since the severing of ties with
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea are at odds over at least six areas along
their common border. The latest round of border clashes broke out
in last May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Government Sets up Task Force to Fight Doping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- French government decided on
Tuesday to set up a task force to fight doping in the sports.
</P>
<P>
The announcement by Health Minister Bernard Kouchner and
Sports Minister Marie-George Buffet came in the wake of the Tour
de France which was plagued by drug scandals.
</P>
<P>
The working group includes leading figures from sports
medicine, law and sociology. Jean-Paul Escande, former president
of the National Commission against Doping, and Olivier Rousselle,
Head of Requisitions at the State Council, are the group's
co-presidents.
</P>
<P>
The group will make a preliminary report in mid-October and
present its final recommendations by April 1999, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
