<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Severe Storms Kill Five, Black Out Half Million in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Severe thunderstorms with
wind up to 160 kilometers per hour lashed the Northeast of the
United States Monday, killing five people and blacking out more
than 500,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
Two waves of storms caused damage in parts of Pennsylvania, New
York, New Jersey, West Virginia and Connecticut, one early in the
morning and the second in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Tornadoes were reported in parts of New York, New Jersey and
West Virginia. Gusts estimated at 160 kph broke a wind gauge at
Chatham, New Jersey, the weather service said. Hail more than 5
centimeters in diameter was reported at Muncy, Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
Flying debris killed two men early in the morning at the New
York State Fair in Syracuse. One woman was killed by a falling
tree in New York City during the afternoon and a man drowned when
wind capsized his boat in Great South Bay, off Long Island, New
York. Another boater drowned during the afternoon on Sandy Hook
Bay off New Jersey, the Associated Press said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 500,000 customers were rendered without power in the
storms, including 150,000 in central New York state, 143,000 in
the New York City area, 120,000 in New Jersey, 110,000 in
Pennsylvania, 9,000 in Connecticut and 3,000 in West Virginia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
