<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- A state ban on shrimp fishing by trawlers has
drastically reduced the quantity of shrimp on sale and triggered a
price hike in Kuwait, Tuesday's local daily Arab Times reported.
</P>
<P>
The ban from the Public Authority for Agricultural Affairs and
Fish Resources has put 120 owners of trawlers and hundreds of
fishermen out of work, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Salem Failakawi, a fish market supervisor, said the price of a
shrimp basket had risen to 130 to 200 U.S. dollars compared with
around 80 U.S. dollars per basket before the ban was imposed.
</P>
<P>
Retail price for large sized shrimp was nearly 10 U.S. dollars
per kilogram, some 30 percent higher than that during last fishing
season.
</P>
<P>
Some trawlers have already lodged complaints against the ban.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey has started the bidding process for eight
power plants employing the build-operate-transfer method (BOT),
the Daily News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Many large Turkish companies including Koc, Entes, Ihlas,
Alarko, Okan, Marubeni, Guris and Suzer, along with some foreign
companies such as Unit International, ABB, AES and Gasprom are
among the tenderers.
</P>
<P>
If completed, the eight power plants will have a generating
capacity of 4,287 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources has said that
other companies which are interested in the projects have to
present their feasibility studies to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
MANAMA -- Bahrain will host from September 13 to 16 the second
Middle East petrol-tech convention and exhibition at the Bahrain
international fair grounds, with the participation of a number of
refining and petrochemical experts the world over.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Egyptian daily "Alam Al Yom" quoted the chairman of
the convention organizing committee Daifulla Al Otaiba as saying
that the convention is the second in series of events successfully
launched in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that over 600 experts would participate in the
convention to discuss more than 100 scientific and technical
working papers presented by 20 countries. They cover all aspects
of refining as well as the production of chemical matters.
</P>
<P>
He further stated that the production of petrochemicals by the
Gulf Cooperation Council member states accounts for 20 percent of
world production.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The governor of Suez Mamdouh Al Zohairi has agreed to
allocate 20,000 square meters in the industrial zone in Adabiya
for producting cardboard, with total investments of 850 million
Egyptian pounds (250 million U.S. dollars) for the first phase of
the project.
</P>
<P>
The new project will produce 150,000 tonnes of cardboard a
year, 50 percent of which will be exported.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's "Alam Al Yom" quoted Zohairi as saying that studies
are under way for the establishment of a garbage processing plant
to deal with the project's waste.
</P>
<P>
Zohairi added that the factory will provide 150 job
opportunities which will rise to 300 with the completion of the
second phase.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has refused to discuss with the European Union
(EU) the allocation of a quota of textile exports in return for
reducing the margin of dumping.
</P>
<P>
According to Tuesday's "Alam Al Yom," Egyptian Minister of
Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili pointed out that Egypt's approval
would mean its admission of dumping, an issue rejected by Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt is intensifying contacts with the six EU
countries opposed to Egypt. Two EU countries are neutral
ones. Seven EU countries support Egypt's stance. EU's voting on
the issue is due to take place later this month.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian and Palestinian officials decided Tuesday to
call for a trilateral meeting soon with Israel to establish a
clear mechanism that can facilitate the trade exchange, mainly
agricultural products exchange, between Jordan and the Palestinian
self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
According to Jordanian Minister of Agriculture Mejhim Khreisha
and his Palestinian counterpart Hikmat Zeid, the meeting will
convene agricultural and trade experts from the three sides, but
its date and venue have not been finalized yet, Jordan's official
news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
Israel keeps monopoly over the Palestinian market. Other
countries are difficult to enter the market if Israel does not
give the green light. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Remain an Open Market: Financial Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Financial Secretary Donald
Tsang of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region promised here
Tuesday that the government will surrender its powers of
intervention and retreat from the market once the crisis is over.
</P>
<P>
Tsang made the assurance in an interview with Radio-3's "Hong
Kong Today" program Tuesday about a package of measures taken by
the government to tackle manipulations in the foreign exchange,
stock and futures markets.
</P>
<P>
"I have explained again that we had no alternative but to make
incursions in the market," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
"Those are all transparent measures which we hope would reduce
the incidence of such an incursion in the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have explained clearly that this market, unlike others, is
regulated not only by our own law but by the Basic Law which says
quite clearly that the market we have has to be open and it also
states very clearly for the foreign exchanges to continue its
universal circulation," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"So we have explained that in extreme circumstances under which
we have to make a departure, and we have explained why we
hopefully would not have made such an incursion in the future," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The government Monday put forward a 30-point package of
measures to tackle market speculation.
</P>
<P>
Among the measures are stiffer penalties for illegal short
selling, and the Stock Exchange will also crack down on brokerages
which failed to settle trades on time.
</P>
<P>
They form part and parcel of the package that together with the
measures that the government announced last Saturday in relation
to the Monetary Authority.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said he believed that they would basically form a
reasonable package to deal with improper trading in the stock and
shares market, particularly the futures market.
</P>
<P>
However, Tsang said that the permanent solution is not entirely
rested with Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that there has to be some discipline, universally
and internationally agreed discipline in regulating the flow of
funds which
are used for speculative purposes of this kind," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
"We have been advocating this and so are many other countries
in Asia. And so as the International Monetary Fund. But somehow we
have not yet come to a consensus about how to proceed," he
continued.
</P>
<P>
For that reason, economies like Hong Kong and many others, have
to deal with it on their own, he said.
</P>
<P>
"What we did over the last few weeks are things which we would
not have done, but unfortunately circumstances are such that we
have to take these protective measures in order to guard our own
systems," Tsang noted.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said that he was very glad that those measures the
government has put in place seem to be working and the market
welcomed them.
</P>
<P>
"But as I have said many many times, speculators are part and
parcel of an open market structure and we cannot avoid them and in
certain way they are good for the market," he said.
</P>
<P>
"What we do not want to have are manipulators in the market,
who are trying to do a double play, both on the currency market as
well as the securities market by dictating what they believe to be
the real interest rates in HK," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Those people are the sort of people we have to deal with and I
am sure that they have seen that we have sufficient determination
to deal with them, up to the point that we have made the
incursions in the securities market," Tsang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Congratulates DPRK on 50th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
Tuesday sent a congratulatory message to Kim Jong Il, leader of
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), on the occasion
of the 50th anniversary of the founding of DPRK.
</P>
<P>
"The founding the Democratic People's Republic of Korea opened
a new era in Korean history. The Korean people have since embarked
on the road of building a socialist country by maintaining
independence and keeping the initiative in their own hands," Jiang
said in his message to Kim Jong Il, chairman of the National
Defense Commission of DPRK.
</P>
<P>
In the past 50 years, the Korean people have achieved great
progress in defending their national sovereignty and in building
socialism under the leadership of late President Kim Il Sung,
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
In pursuing an independent foreign policy of peace and
friendship and developing friendly relations with all the peoples
of the world, the Korean people have made positive contributions
to the peace and stability in Asia and the rest of the world as
well, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Now that the Korean people are more closely united around the
Worker's Party of Korea led by comrade Kim Jong Il, they are
working hard to advance socialist construction and the cause for
the peaceful reunification of the nation, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"I am glad to see every achievement made by the Korean people,
and wish your country ever greater success," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations, Jiang said that under the present
complicated international situation, it is both in the fundamental
interest of the two peoples and conducive to regional peace and
stability to further consolidate and develop the traditional
friendship and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that under the joint efforts of the two sides,
traditional Sino-Korean friendly and cooperative relations will be
improved even more so," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
