<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Condemns Turkish Cypriots' Proposal of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' political leaders
Tuesday unanimously condemned a confederation proposal by the
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash as a solution to the island's
14-year-old division.
</P>
<P>
The condemnation was made at a four-hour meeting of the
National Council, the top advisory body of President on the
handling of the Cyprus problem, which comprises leaders of five
political parties in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
"Denktash's statements constitute a repetition, a culmination,
a codification and further worsening of earlier known intransigent
positions of the Turkish side," government spokesman Christos
Stylianides said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The council meeting came a week after Denktash proposed the
reunification of the Mediterranean island in a confederation
"between two sovereign and equal states."
</P>
<P>
Stylianides told reporters that the proposal contravenes
relevant U.N. resolutions, the 1977 and 1979 agreements between
the Greek and Turkish Cypriots and the spirit of international law.
</P>
<P>
The two agreements envisage the establishment of a bi-zonal,
bi-communal federation in Cyprus in line with relevant U.N.
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared the breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which is recognized only by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
U.N. has been trying for decades to unify the island through a
bi-communal federation formula, but the Turkish Cypriots opted out
of peace talks a year ago to protest against a European Union
decision to begin access talks with Cyprus, but not their close
ally Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said the National Council will see if to bring the
problem before the U.N. General Assembly and the Security Council
for discussion after President Glafcos Clerides' visit to New York.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and other senior officials will fly to New York later
this month to address the U.N. General Assembly on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
