<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Urges for Accord on Working Hours for Truckers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission is
urging that an accord on working hours be established for truckers
and coach drivers since a one-day strike by French truckers
blocked inter-European Union trade.
</P>
<P>
European Employment Commissioner Padraig Flynn and Transport
Commissioner Neil Kinnock hoped the parties involved could reach
an agreement on shorter working hours before September 30.
</P>
<P>
A meeting for those concerned is scheduled for September 18.
</P>
<P>
If no accord is reached, then the commission, the executive
body of the 15-nation union, will have to introduce its own
proposal on working hours for truck and coach drivers, or what the
commission describes as mobile road transport.
</P>
<P>
A spokesperson for Commissioner Flynn told the press on Tuesday
that the commission has proposed a regular working week of 48
hours and a maximum time of 60 hours per week.
</P>
<P>
Flynn and Kinnock said in a joint statement: "The commission
recognizes the strength of feeling behind this current (French)
protest.
</P>
<P>
"It is eager to get a firm agreement between both sides of the
industry on the critical issue of working time in road transport."
</P>
<P>
But, the commissioners stressed, the social partners have an
essential role to play in shaping the framework for working time
rules at a European level, and they should grasp the opportunity
in a constructive manner.
</P>
<P>
The commission worked out a directive on working time for the
non-mobile road transport sector in July last year.
</P>
<P>
There are approximately 3.5 million people involved in the road
transport industry in the European Union. The total includes both
the non-mobile and mobile transport workers.
</P>
<P>
French truckers launched a multi-day strike last year just
before the World Cup soccer tournament was scheduled to start in
their country.
</P>
<P>
The strike caused a road transport havoc and resulted in a
blockade for the inter-European community trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
