<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Capable of Combating Economic Risks: State Councillor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China has developed a strong
capacity to combat economic risks, State Councillor Wu Yi told
a seminar on investment strategies of transnationals here
today.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the remark while delivering a speech titled "The Asian
Financial Crisis and China's Economic Development" at the seminar.
</P>
<P>
The state councillor said that though the Asian financial
crisis has to some extent worsened the international environment
for developing China's economy, putting great pressure on China's
drive to realize its economic growth target for this year, the
country's economy has continued to maintain a steady growth.
</P>
<P>
China's steady economic development despite the Asian financial
crisis has also proved that the policies and measures the central
Chinese government has put into effect are correct and effective,
Wu noted.
</P>
<P>
According to her, in the first six months of this year China's
gross domestic product (GDP) went up by seven percent over the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
From January to July, China witnessed increases of 7.8 percent
in industrial added value and 15.6 percent in investment by
state-owned organizations in fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
In July alone, the increase in investment for fixed assets was
22.8 percent, which gave an impetus to the development of the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, retail sales of
consumer commodities went up by 8.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, China also scored 179.487 billion
U.S. dollars-worth of foreign trade, up 4.2 percent over the same
period of last year, and chalked up 26.7 billion U.S. dollars in
favorable balance of trade, a rise of 6.2 billion U.S. dollars
over last year's level.
</P>
<P>
Also during the same period, China newly signed contracts
involving 28 billion U.S. dollars in overseas investment, up 7.3
percent, and had an inflow of 23.9 billion U.S. dollars of
overseas investment, which kept the level at that of the same
period of last year, coupled with an improvement in the industrial
structure of overseas-funded businesses.
</P>
<P>
By early August, China's state foreign exchange reserves stood
at 140.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The state councillor noted that China's economic growth slowed
down in the first six months of the year, but it is considered a
high growth speed from the global perspective. And the entire
spectrum of foreign trade and economic cooperation also kept a
steady growth.
</P>
<P>
Under the adverse impact of the Asian financial crisis, the
central Chinese government, with a view to maintaining a
coordinated development in China's economy and stabilizing the
Asian and the eventually the global economies, has tried hard to
safeguard the stability of the Chinese currency, although it
suffered severe losses by doing so, said Wu.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, China has also actively participated in the
rescue package plans organized by the IMF, and provided some Asian
countries with funds and materials in accordance with China's
ability, making a due contribution to stabilizing the Asian and
world economies, said Wu, adding that the central government's
responsible attitude has won wide appreciation from the
international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
