<HEADLINE> Pak Not to Be Responsible for Engineered Default: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Commerce Minister
Ishaq Dar Tuesday said Pakistan would not be responsible for any
default that may be engineered to punish it for its nuclear
detonations.
</P>
<P>
"This will be a unique default, if happens at all, for it would
not be for home-grown reasons but would be imposed from outside,"
Dar told the National Assembly while speaking on the resolution
sought to be moved by the opposition with regard to the
stabilization of the Pakistani currency.
</P>
<P>
"We have to pay the price for our sovereignty. It would be a
default, if happens at all, not because of domestic reasons but
would be done due to malafide and engineered moves from outside,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Before the nuclear tests, he said, the government was supposed
to pay 7.7 billion dollars loans by June 1999 and the country
would have a surplus of 1.9 billion dollars in its reserves even
after paying back these loans.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, all foreign investments inflows have been
dried down after the economic sanctions imposed by the West in the
wake of its nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the devaluation of rupee, he said, the government
would strictly deal with the handful of foreign exchange dealers
who were trying to destabilize the local currency for their
personal benefits.
</P>
<P>
He said the government intends to stabilize the rupee within
reasonable limits and warned stern action would be taken against
those speculators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
