<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frankfurt Airport Bows to EU Competition Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
on Tuesday that the Frankfurt Airport had changed its ground
handling policy to abide by the commission's competition rules.
</P>
<P>
The German airport told the commission, the executive body of
the 15-nation European Union, that it would no longer tie its
customers to the concluded long-term contracts for ground handling
services.
</P>
<P>
The commission adopted last January two decisions requiring the
German airport to bring its monopoly in ramp handling services to
an end.
</P>
<P>
After the Frankfurt Airport became aware that the ground
handling market had to be opened up for competition, it sought to
preserve the substance of its old monopoly by concluding long-term
contracts with its best customers, covering periods of from three
to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
European Competition Commissioner Karel van Miert immediately
told the Frankfurt Airport that its practice was contrary to the
community competition rules.
</P>
<P>
The commission said in a written statement issued on Tuesday
that the Frankfurt Airport had told it that the airport would
allow its customers to terminate without penalty any contracts
already concluded and that it would not conclude any more such
contracts in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
