<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Adopts Child Protection Authority Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A National Child Protection
Authority Bill was adopted by Sri Lankan parliament Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, the government will set up a centralized agency
to coordinate and implement tough laws aimed at protecting
children's rights.
</P>
<P>
The parliament voted unanimously to create a National Child
Authority (NCPA) which will be charged with functions earlier
handled by several ministers, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
An annual report on details of the NCPA would be presented in
parliament and accordingly legislators would be granted an
opportunity to discuss problems, Justice Minister G.L. Peiris said
in Parliament Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister earlier said this is considered one of the most
important pieces of legislation which will fill in the gaps in the
existing law on the rights of children and child abuse.
</P>
<P>
There were reportedly 30,000 abused children in the country and
about a third of them were being "bought and sold" by paedophiles.
 
</P>
