<HEADLINE> Flood-Threatened Siberian Tigers to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-two Siberian tigers that
had to be evacuated because of raging floods this summer will be
returned to their home in one month's time, sources said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The tigers had lived in an artificial "nature reserve" north of
this capital of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, which was
only 400 meters away from the threatened dykes of the Songhua
River.
</P>
<P>
Siberian tigers are animals on the verge of extinction. It is
estimated that only dozens of them are still living in the wild.
</P>
<P>
From August 10, floods on the river endangered the dykes as
well as the safety of these big cats, who are being trained at the
reserve to return to live in the wild in the future.
</P>
<P>
On August 16, the tigers were moved to a special center some
200 km away, where they had to be to locked in cages.
</P>
<P>
"They might feel that their freedom has been taken away," said
Liu Jinchen, who is taking care of the tigers.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the water level of the Songhua River is still above
the danger line, four meters higher than the tigers' home which is
now deep in water. The drainage work will last at least one month,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that the tigers can return to the reserve safely,
animal keepers are working as dyke keepers, patrolling along the
river round the clock.
</P>
<P>
As the water level recedes, the dyke might face the danger of
collapse, the local government has warned.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another special reserve is being built nearby for
24 baby tigers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
