<HEADLINE> Passports of Nepalese Delegation Stolen in S.Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 8 (Xinhua) -- All the diplomatic passports
of the 21-member Nepalese delegation including that of Prime
Minister Girija Prasad Koirala were stolen in Durban, South
Africa, an informed source said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The delegation comprising Nepalese press representatives was
leaving Durban for Johannesburg when it found on September 4 at
the Durban International Airport that the bag containing all the
passports was stolen, a Nepalese journalist who accompanied the
delegation said.
</P>
<P>
The delegation went to Durban to attend the 12th Summit of the
Non-Aligned Movement held on September 2-3.
</P>
<P>
The South African police tried in vain to find the passports,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that on the advice of the South African Foreign
Ministry, Nepali Foreign Ministry officials in the delegation
wrote letters of certificate for all the members to serve as
provisional passports.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of passports, the Nepali delegation could not
exchange its traveler's checks in Johannesburg and Dubai, the
United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
During the seven-hour stopover in Dubai, the rest of the
delegation members were not allowed to go outside the airport
except the prime minister, his daughter, the finance minister and
Nepal's ambassador to Egypt, the journalist said.
</P>
<P>
Later Prime Minister Koirala paid a three-day visit to Qatar
without a passport, but the Qatar government made all the
arrangements, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
