<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Researchers Claim to Develop Anti-malarial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- By exploiting a compound
isolated from a Chinese herb, Indian researchers claimed to have
developed an anti-malarial drug to cure cerebral malaria, the
Press Trust of India (PTI) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The drug, arteether, was jointly developed by scientists at the
Central Drug Research Institute (CDRI) and the Central Institute
of Medicinal and Aromatic Plants (CIMAP), according to the PTI.
</P>
<P>
The drug can project people against "palsmodium falciparum"
mosquitoes and cure about 98 percent patients with no untoward
reactions, said a recent CDRI report.
</P>
<P>
Under a post marketing study, a total of 300 patients from
several states were administered with the drug and most of the
patients were cured without any side effects, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
Since most of the anti-malarial drugs introduced in India were
found to have adverse side effects, Indian Drug Controller General
had earlier made most marketing surveillance mandatory for all new
drugs to observe the adverse reactions.
</P>
<P>
Arteether, developed in a seven year project, was granted
marketing permit last year.
</P>
<P>
The key ingredient of the drug is a compound called artemisinin
or qinghaosu, as it was known in Chinese medical text isolated
from the herb "artemisia annual".
</P>
<P>
The mother plant was cultivated in the Kashmir valley to
produce artemisinin, said PTI. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
