-- In Atlanta, the cradle of the nation's civil rights
movement, thousands of black youths gathered on historic Auburn
Avenue Monday, vowing to launch a grass-roots movement to end a
feeling of apathy they say has gripped many in their generation.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton's private lawyer asked that Kenneth W.
Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, let him review at least
a week in advance any report Starr submitts to Congress, in a sign
the White House is readying a defense against possible impeachment
hearings.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Greenspan said the Fed no longer sees inflation as its
primary near-term worry. His remarks, emphasizing the threat from
global economic stress, suggested that a reduction in U.S.
short-term interest is now more likely than it was at the
beginning of summer. Meanwhile, Rubin and the IMF chief pressured
Japan to shore up its sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
USA Today:
</P>
