to Qatar, Koirala said that Nepal neglected relations with small
countries by giving priority to ties with big countries.
</P>
<P>
"We have to keep relations with the Gulf countries by changing
our foreign policy," he stressed, adding that the Gulf countries
have very good economic potentials.
</P>
<P>
After attending the 12th summit of the Non-Aligned Movement
(NAM) held on September 2-3 in Durban, South Africa, Koirala paid
a three-day visit to Qatar, the first by a Nepalese prime minister
to the country and the region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 Nepalese are working in the Gulf countries,
with about 30,000 in Qatar alone.
</P>
<P>
Nepal and Qatar had agreed to work together to foster bilateral
relations for further boosting economic and trade links, promoting
joint investment in tourism, industry, manufacturing and financial
sectors and manpower supply to Qatar through government agencies,
the official RSS news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Koirala said that he had invited his Qatar counterpart Sheikh
Abdullah Bin Khalifa Al-Thani to visit Nepal.
</P>
<P>
On the NAM summit, he said that Nepal's positions on
South-South cooperation, poverty alleviation and special
facilities for the least developed and land-locked countries were
written into the Durban Declaration.
</P>
<P>
He said that the summit was very positive.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister added that while in South Africa, he handed
over a letter from Nepalese King Birendra to South African
President Nelson Mandela inviting him to visit Nepal. 
</P>
