<HEADLINE> Green Action in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province,
one of the country's most populous regions in the lower reaches of
the Yellow River, has begun a massive environmental protection
campaign, the "trans-century green action."
</P>
<P>
The province plans to carry out the green action in the next
three years, focusing on protecting and improving an environment
which has long been threatened by inappropriate human activities.
</P>
<P>
The province recently made public eight cases involving illegal
logging and the killing of precious animals, as part of its effort
to crack down on illegal activities related to environmental
protection, the provincial forestry department director Cai
Qiufang said.
</P>
<P>
The province will take strong measures against criminal
activities, impose a logging ban, and plant more trees, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
In recent decades, many forests in the province have been
forced to give way to grain planting, mining, sand gathering and
housing construction, said Cai.
</P>
<P>
As a result, about 20 percent of the province's
150,000-square-kilometer area has been suffering from soil
erosion, and 14 of its 17 cities and prefectures have been
aversely affected by wind and sand to various degrees.
</P>
<P>
Flood control experts say that deforestation along the
country's major rivers has caused serious erosion, raising
riverbeds and partially resulting in the summer flooding which has
affected 29 provinces, cities and autonomous regions in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
