<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo Summit Ends Without Cease-fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A southern African summit on
the Congolese (K) conflict ended at Victoria Falls Tuesday
without agreement on a cease-fire, according to reports from the
Zimbabwean town.
</P>
<P>
Seven presidents including three backing Congolese President
Laurent kabila's government and two opposing it gathered for a
second round of talks Tuesday, promising an immediate end to the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
However, four hours later, the rebel delegation led by Arthur
Z'ahidi Ngoma, Deputy President of the Congolese Democratic
Coalition, left the summit venue without having met face to face
with Kabila or his backers, vowing to fight on.
</P>
<P>
"We are going back home now to do one thing only, to intensify
our campaign against Kabila," Ngoma told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no cease-fire before Kabila negotiates with us
directly," Ngoma said as he left the conference site.
</P>
<P>
Namibian Foreign Minister Theo Ben Gurirab, who earlier
promised that a cease-fire would be implemented across Congo (K)
Tuesday, said he was not disappointed.
</P>
<P>
"What more did you expect. We've had the presidents sitting
around a table and talking while their armies are fighting. This
is an achievement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the Organization of African Unity Salim
Ahmed Salim read a statement after the summit calling for an
early end to the fighting in Congo and saying Kabila had promised
to "broaden the political space" in his country.
</P>
<P>
"We believe ... there must be an end to war in the Democratic
Republic of Congo. We therefore call for an immediate end to
hostilities," the seven leaders said in their statement.
</P>
<P>
Salim said the defense ministers of Zambia, Congo and its
backers, Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia, and those from rebel
allies Rwanda and Uganda would meet in Addis Ababa Thursday to
explore cease-fire options.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba chaired the summit and
said all the participants agreed on the need for a cease-fire and
recognized Kabila as Democratic Congo's legitimate ruler.
</P>
<P>
"There must be a cease-fire so we can slowly but surely bring
peace to that country," said the Zambian President.
</P>
<P>
Kabila accuses Uganda and Rwanda of invading his country and
refuses to recognize the rebels as an internal movement. The
rebels say Kabila has failed to implement democratic reforms,
running instead a corrupt and nepotistic regime.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers of Banyamulenge or Congolese Tutsis took up arms to
oust Kabila in the east on August 2. On August 20, Zimbabwe,
Angola and Namibia sent troops to rout the rebels in the
southwest but they still control large tracts of land in the
eastern part of Africa's third largest country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
