<HEADLINE> Donations for Flood Victims Top 1.8 Billion RMB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Domestic and foreign donations
for China's flood victims received by the Ministry of Civil
Affairs, Red Cross Society of China and China Charity Federation
(CCF) have exceeded 1.8 billion RMB yuan (about 220 million US
dollars), the Civil Affairs Ministry announced here today.
</P>
<P>
By Monday, the Civil Affairs Ministry had received 1.19 billion
yuan in donations, including some 90 million yuan from foreign
governments and individuals, as well as international
non-governmental organizations, while the Red Cross Society of
China and the CCF had received over 154 million yuan and 470
million yuan, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials said that they have already allocated 290
million yuan in donated money and donated materials worth 630
million yuan to the flood-hit areas nationwide, adding that the
Red Cross Society and the CCF have also delivered most of the
donations they have received to the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Fan Baojun, deputy minister of civil affairs, today received
from the Kuwaiti ambassador to China three million US dollars,
which was said to be the largest foreign government donation for
China's flood victims since many parts of the country were hit by
the worst flooding in decades this summer.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials said that today's donation was the ninth the
ministry had received from foreign governments. The eight other
nations providing assistance were the United States, Japan,
Republic of Korea, Singapore, Israel, Cuba, Yugoslavia and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The government of Cuba donated one million units of hepatitis B
vaccine, valued at some 1.15 million US dollars, for use in the
flooded areas, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
