<HEADLINE> HK Government Committed to Maintain Its Free Market: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwa stressed here Tuesday that the government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region will continue its efforts to
maintain Hong Kong as a very free market.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a media session after attending the Executive
Council meeting, Tung said that a series of measures announced by
the financial secretary and the chief executive of the Monetary
Authority in the last few days aimed at making sure that "our
linked exchange rate is as strong as ever, and that our stock and
futures markets can operate in an orderly and transparent manner."
</P>
<P>
"This is done to avoid our markets being manipulated," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Hong Kong is one of the freest markets in the
world, Tung said: "We aim to maintain it that way."
</P>
<P>
He explained that the reason why the government entered the
market was because it saw a clear linkage between activities in
the futures market and stock market on the one hand and the
foreign currency market on the other.
</P>
<P>
"We did this to correct distortions that had been created by
those who were manipulating our market and nothing else," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Tung emphasized the importance of recovering a stable interest
rate environment as Hong Kong is going through a difficult period
of adjustment.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that these measures which have been taken
will be widely supported by the community.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on whether he is concerned that the
regulations might affect Hong Kong's freedom, Tung said: "I am not
concerned at all because i think these regulations are made really
to improve our transparency, to improve the way we will regulate
ourselves to ensure that we continue to be a very free market, and
to ensure that our market will not be manipulated."
</P>
<P>
The 7-point plan to strengthen the local currency peg and the
30-point measures to curb breaches of securities regulations were
announced by the government respectively on Saturday and Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Hopes to Help Angola in Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has expressed its
desire to engage in the post-war reconstruction in Angola, O
Jornal de Angola reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper quoted Vietnamese Ambassador to Luanda Ta
Nguyen as saying here recently that his country is willing to
pass its rich experience in post-war restoration of production
and industrialization to the Angolan people.
</P>
<P>
Nguyen noted that the Vietnamese government would like to
cooperate with Angola in the fields of economy and trade.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is interested in investing in Angola's trade,
agriculture, civil construction, transport and fishery, the
ambassador said, adding that priority should be placed on the
development of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He said that Vietnam can teach Angolan farmers in rice
growing. The southeastern Asian country ranks the second among
the rice producers and the fifth among the rice exporters in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Vietnam hopes to sell Angola its food products and
manufactured goods while buying petroleum products from the
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
However, Nguyen pointed out that currently there is no trade
relationship between the two governments. There are only
contacts between the small enterprises of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador disclosed that there are now about 400
Vietnamese citizens working in Angola as experts in health care
and education.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam was the second country recognizing the independence of
Angola, next only to Brazil. And Angola is the only sub-Saharan
country which has embassy in Hanoi since 1976. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
