<HEADLINE> Thailand to Waive Charge for Int'l Transit Passengers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- International passengers in
transit/transfer at Bangkok International Airport will be exempted
from an airport service charge should they return to the airport
within a 12-hour period.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation, to be effective from October 1 this year,
will waive the 500-bath (12.5 U.S. dollars) fee for
transit/transfer passengers who temporarily depart the airport,
the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT) said in a statement
available here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The transit/transfer passengers are only required to notify
authorities and fill out a request form upon their arrival.
</P>
<P>
TAT Governor Seree Wangpaichitr said the regulation amendment
could well compliment the ongoing Amazing Thailand 1998-1999
campaign. "This is among a number of our initiatives to make
Thailand a bit more attractive," he said.
</P>
<P>
TAT and the Association of Thai Travel Agents (ATTA) are
preparing suggested tour programs for those wishing to visit
interesting attractions. Itineraries are being tailored, taking
into account the duration of possible activities.
</P>
<P>
At least 4-5 hours are needed for the suggested excursions,
which feature nearby spots such as the fruit and vegetable
wholesale market and various shopping complexes. Longer transit
time is for more distant places, i.e. Bang Sai Handicraft Center
in Ayutthaya, Nonthaburi or downtown Bangkok. The tour package
will be reasonably priced.
</P>
<P>
Passengers can opt to travel on their own, provided that the
12-hour period is strictly observed. TAT will distribute a
guidebook recommending attractions, tips and advice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
