<HEADLINE> Palestinians Blast Israel's Anti-Egypt Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A Palestinian diplomat said on
Tuesday that Israel has launched an anti-Egypt campaign with
ulterior motives, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Ambassador in Cairo Zohdi al Kodra shrugged off as
"tendentious and suspicious" Israel's allegations that Egypt
pressured Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat during his recent visit
to Cairo to reject any agreement with Israel on the further
withdrawal from the West Bank, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt is the Palestinians' big brother because of its crucial
and central role, global and regional weight and also its genuine
desire for peace and stability in the Middle East," Kodra said.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt has never turned its back on the Palestinian cause, and
it has never interfered in the Palestinian decisions," he added.
</P>
<P>
The government of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is
"wrong" if it thinks that it can impose a status quo on the Arab
world and the Palestinian people, he said.
</P>
<P>
He praised the constant coordination between Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak and Arafat to realize a just and comprehensive peace
and restore the legitimate rights of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks are stuck over the overdue
Israeli troop pullback from the West Bank. Israel and the
Palestinians gave different accounts of the outcomes of recent
contacts and blamed each other for the gaps.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has stressed that any agreement has to be balanced and
should not sacrifice the interest of either side.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Netanyahu said that he briefed
Mubarak Monday on the latest developments in the peace process
over the telephone.
</P>
<P>
He will also dispatch two top aides to Cairo Wednesday for
further talks on the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations. 
</P>
