<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Bronze Museum Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China's first museum
specializing in the exhibition of ancient bronze ware opened today
in the city of Baoji in northwest China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the museum started in 1994, and cost 20
million yuan (about 2.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 27-meter-high main building was designed in the shape of an
ancient bronze cooking vessel.
</P>
<P>
China's Bronze Age began some 3,000 years ago. It was a
splendid period in world civilization. The Shang and Zhou
dynasties were famous for their superb bronze wares which both
kings and commoners used for cooking, eating and drinking and
holding religious rites.
</P>
<P>
The museum opened with a special exhibition on rare relics
excavated from tombs of the Zhou and Qin dynasties, more than
2,000 years ago. The dynasties' capitals were located in what is
now Shaanxi.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the museum will serve as a storehouse and an
exhibition center as well as a research institute.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
