<HEADLINE> More Macao Residents Act as Civil Servants: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The localization of civil
servants in Macao has scored new headway, according to officials
attending a meeting held here on Tuesday by the Sino-Portuguese
Joint Liaison Group (JLG).
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 27 percent of the officials at the department level
in the Macao government are headed by local Macao residents, and
73 percent of division chiefs are Macao residents, said Wang
Xi'an, Chinese representative of the Sino-Portuguese JLG.
</P>
<P>
Portugal has made a promise that approximately all government
departments will have been headed by Macao residents by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xi'an noted that there are only more than three months
left for the promise to be materialized and a lot of work has to
be done, expressing his wish that the Portuguese side keeps
promise.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the localization of laws in Macao, Wang said that
the localization of Civil Law, Civil Procedure Law and Commercial
Law is well under way and is expected to be completed this year.
And consultations on some other laws can be conducted next year.
</P>
<P>
Wang added that the use of Chinese as an official language is
still not enough in some administrative, judicial and legislative
affairs in Macao. The Chinese side will continue to make the
Portuguese side strengthen the use of Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Moitinho de Almeida, Portuguese representative of the
Sino-Portuguese JLG, told reporters on Tuesday that Portugal would
keep its promise of localizing civil servants of the Macao
government by the end of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
