<HEADLINE> Turkish FM to Visit Iran over Afghan Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem is scheduled to pay a four-day visit to Tehran next
week for talks on the latest developments in Afghanistan, the
official IRNA news agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
IRNA quoted informed sources as saying that Turkey has voiced
willingness to consult with Iran on ways of solving the Afghan
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Cem's visit comes after a trip to Turkey Monday by
Afghanistan's ousted president, Burhanuddin Rabbani, who called
for international measures against his country's fundamentalist
Taliban militia, it said.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani and his Northern Alliance suffered a serious setback
last month when the Taliban captured Mazari Sharif, a major
stronghold of the alliance in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, which drove Rabbani out of capital Kabul in 1996,
is controlling most areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is concerned with Taliban's advance, fearing that the
group advocating strict Islamic rule would spread Islamic
fundamentalism to Central Asian republics, which enjoy close
relations with Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, though a predominantly Muslim country, maintains
secularism.
</P>
<P>
It is widely rumored that Tehran and Ankara are encouraged to
arm Afghan refugees in Iran in response to their request to fight
against the Taliban militia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
