<HEADLINE> HK Newspapers Laud Government's New Market Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Many newspapers in Hong Kong
issued editorials or commentaries Tuesday to welcome the
government's 30-point new measures to curb market speculation,
including expulsion of brokers who breach Hong Kong's trading
regulations.
</P>
<P>
Ming Pao Daily News said in an editorial that the new measures
aiming to maintain a good order of the securities and futures
market and increase its transparency are "moderate and
reasonable."
</P>
<P>
It is believed that it would not be difficult for these
measures to win the support of Legislative Council members and
the public as well, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Under the new proposals, brokers who repeatedly breach rules on
short-selling will receive heavy penalties and risk losing their
stock exchange membership.
</P>
<P>
An article published by Hong Kong Standard said the new
measures will "add strength to the government's anti-speculation
drive by providing stricter rules no short-selling in the stock
market."
</P>
<P>
Ta Kung Pao issued a commentary entitled "Goal of Defending
Linked Exchange Rate System, Stabilizing Market Bound to Be
Realized."
</P>
<P>
It said the sharp rise in the Hang Seng Index Monday to 8,076
points, the third highest so far this year, together with the fall
of the interbank rate, demonstrates that the order of Hong Kong's
financial market seems to start its recovery to normal.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wei Po said the seven-point measures announced by the
government at the weekend to strengthen the currency board system
have achieved remarkable results.
</P>
<P>
The sharp rise in the Hang Seng Index and lower interbank rate
fully show that the government's intervention in the stock market
is correct and necessary and the foundation of Hong Kong's stock
market is sound and healthy.
</P>
<P>
The government's 30-point measures to tighten up securities and
futures market are a result of summing up experiences by the
government to curb speculations, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
