<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Slightly Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
Tuesday slightly weaker but off earlier lows as buying from Tokyo
markets offered support.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed the session in Sydney at 59.34 U.S.
cents, down marginally from 59.36 U.S. cents Monday night. It had
earlier dipped to 58.76 U.S. cents after opening below the 59.00
U.S. cent mark.
</P>
<P>
"With the U.S. dollar/Japanese yen exchange rate bouncing off
131.00 yen today, we've seen Aussie/yen buying come out in force,
which drove the Aussie up and really kept it supported all day,"
said Stuart Moore, manager of foreign exchange trading with St
George Bank.
</P>
<P>
A great deal of movement is expected Tuesday night as U.S.
markets return from their Labor Day long weekend.
</P>
<P>
"The big thing will be tonight and the Dow, we've had two very
good days in the Asian stock market so people will be watching the
Dow after the holiday in the States," Moore said.
</P>
<P>
"I think (the Australian dollar) will focus mainly on the
strength or the weakness of the U.S. dollar and that will depend
on the Dow," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 78.48 Japanese yen from 78.37
yen and 1.0276 German marks from 1.0236 marks. 
</P>
