<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Weaker in Light Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
consolidated its recent strong gains giving up just 0.5 percent
Tuesday with industrial stocks weighing on the bourse as investors
took profits.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index slipped 14.0 points, or 0.54
percent, to 2555.2 after trading within a range of 2554.0 to
2577.7 during the day, but managed to hold onto most of Monday's
2.6 percent gains.
</P>
<P>
Craig Drummond from JB Were said all eyes would be on the
United States Tuesday night, which will open again after a Labor
Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. is yet to react to Greenspan's comments or the
recovery we've seen in Asian markets, and the weakness in the U.S.
dollar," Drummond said.
</P>
<P>
The focus in local trading Tuesday was again on resources
stocks which continued their recent upward trend, albeit slightly,
with the all resources index adding 1.9 points to 1004.0.
</P>
<P>
Still, the real shine came from the gold stocks which added
29.9 points, or 3.01 percent, to 1021.9 points.
</P>
<P>
The price of the precious metal in Sydney trade closed at
287.65 U.S. dollars an ounce up from Monday's close of 287.45 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the resources sector, diversified miner BHP eased
30 cents to 12.90 Australian dollars, while global miner Rio Tinto
rallied 10 cents to 18.50 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, National Australia Bank added 3.7 cents to
21.457 Australian dollars, while Commonwealth Bank of Australia
lost five cents to 19.90 Australian dollars. ANZ bank rose one
cent to 8.81 Australian dollars and Westpac bank gained 1.6 cents
to 9.366 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 267.28 million shares traded for 771.59
million Australian dollars (457.86 million U.S. dollars), with 388
stocks rising, 317 stocks falling and 258 stocks steady. 
</P>
