<HEADLINE> 74 Shops Looted, Burned in Indonesia's Kebumen Riot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- As many as 74 shops and
warehouses and dozens of vehicles have been looted and burned as
rioting in Kebumen district in Indonesia's Central Java Province
entered its second day Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
One of the burned shops was even located beside the Kebumen
police station which was also torched. Some 15 trucks, 9 public
vehicles and 5 motorcycles have also been burned.
</P>
<P>
Some 74 people have been arrested, 32 of them students, and are
now being questioned by the police, according to Antara News
Agency reports.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the police has tried to disperse the
mobs by firing teargas canisters at them but this only prompted
them to flee to other areas and start looting and burning more
stores belonging to Chinese-Indonesians.
</P>
<P>
More people could be arrested as the riot continues, Chief of
the Kebumen Police Lt. Col. Nuryanto Suharto was quoted by the
report as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nuryanto said the riot began Monday following a quarrel between
the owner of a spare parts shop and an employee.
</P>
<P>
To pacify the riot, Chief of the Central Java Police Maj. Gen.
Nurfaizi said he will hold a dialogue with local religious and
public leaders. 
</P>
