<HEADLINE> German Jobless Rate Dips in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Germany's unemployment rate
dropped slightly to 10.6 percent in August from 10.7 percent a
month ago, confirming a long-predicted trend reversal on the
country's depressed job market, the German Federal Labour Office
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics issued by the labour office Tuesday in
Nuremberg put Germany's jobless total at 4,095,400, down 39,000
from July.
</P>
<P>
When compared with the same month a year ago, the number of
people out of work dropped by 276,600, the office said.
</P>
<P>
"We are now talking about a trend reversal," said labour office
president, Bernhard Jagoda.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the belief that Germany's jobless total is
set to go down below the four million mark in September and
October and would drop by between 200,000 and 300,000 next year.
</P>
<P>
With Germany's national elections just 19 days away, the latest
job data also gave a boost to German Chancellor Helmut Kohl whose
public support has suffered badly from the near-record
unemployment over the past year.
</P>
<P>
The positive development on the job market showed that the
government's reform policies had been effective and companies had
started once again to recruit more workforce, Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD), however,
played down the government's role in cutting unemployment and
stressed that the latest drop in the jobless total was
attributable to a large extent to makeshift job-creation
programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
