<HEADLINE> Bus Drivers in Lagos Go On Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Commercial vehicle
operators Monday went on a strike in Lagos and withdrew their
vehicles from the roads, paralyzing the city all the day.
</P>
<P>
The striking drivers carrying placards and chanting songs
embarked on a peaceful protest against the recognition by the
Lagos state government of officials of the National Union of Road
Transport (NURTW) and Road Transport Employers Association
(RTEAN).
</P>
<P>
The drivers are against the return of the NURTW and RTEAN
officials who, they alleged, have been extorting drivers at the
motorparks, the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The protesters stormed the Victoria Island office of the
Nigerian Television Authority (NTA) in five over-loaded buses and
then went to the office of the Lagos state military administrator
to formally register their grievances.
</P>
<P>
In a nine-point resolution contained in their public notice,
the striking drivers called for the "total disengagement of
NURTW and RTEAN from all motor parks".
</P>
<P>
The notice advised all vehicle owners to keep their vehicles
within their domain until the vexed issues were settled.
</P>
<P>
"All sectors of commercial drivers should cease work as from
Monday, September 7, until further notice," it added.
</P>
<P>
As there were no commercial buses in Lagos Monday, many
commuters had to walk to their destinations and most offices were
empty as workers could not have access to buses to take them to
work.
</P>
<P>
The striking drivers belong to five associations including
Lagos State Taxi Drivers' Association, Urban Commercial Bus
Drivers' Association of Nigeria and Mini-bus Drivers'
Association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
