<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Industrial Output Up Slightly in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial output
picked up slightly, and the three months of flooding stimulated
domestic demand to a certain extent, according to the monthly
report released today by the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that China's industrial added value totalled
158.2 billion yuan, increasing by 7.9 percent on an annual
basis. And the total added value during January-August reached
1.266 trillion yuan, up 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's heavy industry also witnessed a faster growth in
August, encouraged by the Chinese government's scheduled policy of
increasing investment and stimulating domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Statistics revealed that industry's output rose by 7.9 percent,
1.2 percentage points higher than the previous month, while light
industry grew 7.8 percent, 0.9 percentage points lower than the
previous month.
</P>
<P>
Production in the flood-hit regions is rebounding. For
instance, the growth rate of Jiangxi Province was 6.2 percent
higher than the previous month, while that of northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province was 0.2 percentage points lower.
</P>
<P>
The month also registered the highest production-to-sales ratio
of 1998, hitting 97.64 percent, 1.35 percent higher than the
previous month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Ministers: Regional Financial Crisis Should Be  Urgently Addressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Ministers Responsible for
small and medium-scaled enterprises (SMEs) of Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) Tuesday stressed the importance of
urgently addressing the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ministers expressed concern that, if not addressed
urgently, the global contagion effect that is evident now will
exacerbate, a joint statement issued Tuesday at the end of their
two-day meeting held in Petaling Jaya near here said.
</P>
<P>
The impact of regional financial instability on the SMEs was
addressed in depth at the two-day meeting, Malaysian International
Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz told a press conference
at the end of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the ministers strongly endorsed APEC Finance
Ministers' decision to share knowledge and experiences on
approaches to financial market regulations, to consider
establishing a global system of multilateral surveillance of
national financial sector supervisory and regulatory systems and
to develop immediate measures to support SMEs and strengthen
social safety nets in affected economies.
</P>
<P>
The Ministers emphasized that APEC Finance Ministers should
develop the necessary securities and financial market regulatory
framework as soon as possible and agreed that proposals
pertaining to measures to address the financial crisis discussed
at this meeting be conveyed to finance ministers, it said.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that it is important to continue with the
liberalization process and that the present financial turmoil
should not deter progress in this regard.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed the importance of APEC economies taking
measures either individually or collectively to prevent a future
recurrence of the crisis, it said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers encouraged the adoption of specific measures to
address the impact of the crisis on SMEs, which could include
ensuring the availability of trade financing by exports credit
agencies, expansion of industrial supply and subcontracting
business cooperation, better risk assessment capabilities in
relation to credits for SMEs, dissemination of information on
opportunities to build better business linkages for trade and
investment among SMEs and establishment of an interactive business
matching web site.
</P>
<P>
The ministers directed the Policy Level Group (PLG) on SMEs to
work closely with other APEC fora to assist SMEs to overcome their
difficulties as a result of the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was represented by all the 18 APEC members --
Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, Hong Kong, Indonesia,
Japan, Mexico, Malaysia, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea, the
Philippines, Singapore, South Korea, Chinese Taipei, Thailand and
the United States as well as three members-to-be --Peru, Russia
and Vietnam. 
</P>
