<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Ministers Endorse Integrated Plan of Action for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Ministers Responsible for
small and medium-scaled enterprises (SMEs) of Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) Tuesday endorsed at their fifth
meeting in Malaysia the proposed Integrated Plan of Action for SME
Development (SPAN).
</P>
<P>
The SPAN will serve as a set of broad guidelines for SME
development in individual economies, Malaysian International Trade
and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz told a press conference Tuesday
at the end of the two-day meeting held in Petaling Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a joint statement issued at the end of the meeting
said the ministers recognized that SPAN, which builds on the
Framework of SME activities approved by Ministers in 1997,
provided a convenient reference point for review of initiatives,
programs and regulatory framework to promote the development of
SMEs and to plan future action at the individual economy level and
collaborative efforts at the APEC level.
</P>
<P>
The Ministers at the meeting emphasized the importance of
focusing the SME work program on key issues which affect SME
development and on sharing best-practice responsible to these
issues.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized that SPAN should also promote the development
of new entrepreneurs including technopreneurs and recommended the
inclusion of micro enterprises and women entrepreneurs as an
integral part of SPAN.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing environmental friendly and cost effective
technology should be accessible to SMEs, the ministers agreed that
SPAN should also include environmental considerations.
</P>
<P>
In endorsing the SPAN, the ministers acknowledged that it is
not intended to be prescriptive and that adoption would be on a
voluntary basis.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also stressed the importance of private sector
participation in contributing to and carrying out the objectives
of SPAN.
</P>
<P>
The SPAN will be presented to the Ministerial Meeting and
Leaders in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day meeting, the ministers also discussed the
importance of electronic commerce for SMEs, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers reaffirmed the need for specific programs to
facilitate and promote the wider use of electronic commerce by
SMEs and also recognized the need for setting-up appropriate
information infrastructure to ensure business access to electronic
networks.
</P>
<P>
Noting the progress on the implementation of the 17 approved
projects, of which 7 have been completed and the remaining 10 are
at various stages of implementation, the ministers endorsed three
new project proposals including a Strategy for
Internationalization of SMEs in Asia Pacific Area, Training and
Certification for Small Business Counselors, and Electronic
Commerce Impact Study for SMEs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ministers had a dialogue with representatives
of the business sector during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
They also addressed in depth the impact of regional financial
instability on the SMEs and stressed the importance of urgently
addressing the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ministers welcomed New Zealand's offer to host the next
Ministerial Meeting in Christchurch in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting was represented by all the 18 APEC members
-- Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, Hong Kong, Indonesia,
Japan, Mexico, Malaysia, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea, the
Philippines, Singapore, South Korea, Chinese Taipei, Thailand and
the United States as well as three member-designate economies
--Peru, Russia and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
