<HEADLINE> Cote d'Ivoire President Begins Visit to S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Cote d'Ivoire President
Henri Bedie on Tuesday began his four-day state visit to South
Africa for promoting economic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The visit started with a ceremonial welcome from South African
President Nelson Mandela at the latter's official residence in
Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
After that, the two leaders signed a letter of intent on the
promotion of reciprocal trade, in which the two countries vowed
to speedily reach an agreement on the promotion and reciprocal
protection of investments.
</P>
<P>
Bedie received South Africa's highest civilian honor for a
foreigner, the Order of Good Hope, Class I, while Mandela was
invested with the highest honor of the Cote d'Ivoire, the Grand
Cross of the National Order.
</P>
<P>
Bedie, who arrived Monday afternoon in the company of a senior
delegation led by Cote d'Ivoire Foreign Minister Amara Essy, will
address the South African National Assembly Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to meet South African Deputy President
Thabo Mbeki and Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi.
</P>
<P>
The Cote d'Ivoire, the third largest economy in sub-Saharan
Africa, is South Africa's largest trading partner in Francophone
Western Africa with the trade balance in the Cote d'Ivoire's
favor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
