<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Unemployment Yet to Be Worse in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- It was Sunday morning.
Chaichan Wanitthaweewat packed the clothes hangers, laundry
brushes, toothbrushes, clothes pegs and scouring pads he bought
from a wholesale market in Bangkok and headed for a weekend fair,
hoping to make some profits by selling them at retail prices.
</P>
<P>
Chaichan had never imagined he would start his career like this
when he studied ceramics at Sinakharinwirot University.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, his untimely graduation coincided with the
country's worst economic recession in decades. For months, he had
been monitoring newspaper ads for job vacancies and had sent reams
of application letters, but no offer came in.
</P>
<P>
Chaichan is one of the thousands of new university graduates
who became jobless as soon as they left the classroom. The
University Affairs Ministry said there will be 48,000 graduates
like Chaichan at the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
Chaichan is also one of the 2 million people who are ranked
"unemployed" in the country.
</P>
<P>
In fact, with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) forecasting
Thailand's economy to contract by 7 percent this year, and little
improvement in 1999, economists agree that the full impact on
unemployment has yet to be felt.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government predicted earlier this year that
unemployment will reach 2 million this year. However, statistics
for the first half of the year showed that the number of jobless
people has already reached 2 million. Some analysts said the
number may reach 3 million by year-end, or 10 percent of the
country's labor force.
</P>
<P>
What's more, experts said Thailand hasn't really felt the
problems of unemployment yet because job losses just started six
months ago. And people still have their compensation payments.
</P>
<P>
But with prolonged unemployment, once savings run out, social
problems will definitely follow, they said.
</P>
<P>
In the fifth letter of intent reached by Thai government and
IMF, the government pledged to make improvement in the targeting
of its social safety net program by increasing the current year
expenditure for the social program.
</P>
<P>
However, only a robust economic recovery can pull the country
out of the mire of mass unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Medicine prescribed by the IMF for Thailand's economic recovery
hinges on positive external factors, such as export growth and
investment flows, to help replenish foreign reserves, increase
liquidity and spur the recovery.
</P>
<P>
The external environment, however, is far from favorable with
Japan, Russia, Latin America being infected with the flu of
economic crisis and the strongest United States hardly immune.
</P>
<P>
Chartchai Parasuk, a former IMF staff member, said the IMF
prescription for Thailand is risky since everything depends on
external events while the clouds of a global recession are looming
large.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Thailand will be unable to absorb the shock
of 10-15 percent unemployment rates since unemployment will cause
purchasing power and consumption to decline with most of the job
losses occurring in the non-agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
In turn, private production will slow, feeding back in a circle
as more companies go bankrupt or downsize, leading to more
unemployment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Atchana Waiquamdee, director of the economic research
department at the Bank of Thailand, also said with the zero
economic growth next year as forecast by the government and the
IMF, domestic demand and production would continue to fall because
of rising unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government's 1999 fiscal budget calls for a deficit of
3 percent of gross domestic product, used to support additional
spending to help spur employment and ease the social impact of the
recession.
</P>
<P>
However, Atchana said the fiscal deficit spending as targeted
would have little impact on unemployment, considering the increase
in the labor force from newly graduated students.
</P>
<P>
In theory, zero growth should cause employment levels to remain
relatively steady. But declining consumption would force
corporates to restructure, cut costs and downsize, thus increasing
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Though a peddler now, Chaichan still cherishes his dream of
owning and operating a facility where he could put his university
ceramics study to good use.
</P>
<P>
However, at present, what he asks for is a decent job. But even
that seems to be an unreachable dream for the time being. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
