<HEADLINE> NAM Summit to Effect Long-term Influence: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministry spokesman Zhu
Bangzao today lauded the recently concluded 12th summit of the
Non-Aligned Movement as an important meeting at the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
The summit has produced positive results and will undoubtedly
have a long-term effect on the future development of the movement,
Zhu said at today's routine press conference.
</P>
<P>
He termed NAM as an important political force in the world
arena, and said China has always attached great importance to the
movement's constructive role in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Since it became an observer of the movement, China has enjoyed
considerable progress in its relationship with NAM, and
co-operation between the two sides promises broad prospects, he
said.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese delegation headed by Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan
attended the summit convened from August 29 to September 3 in
Durban of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Tang delivered a speech on China's relations with the movement,
and exchanged views with some state leaders on issues of common
interest. This fully demonstrated China's support to developing
countries and the NAM, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
China is fully convinced that under the new world situation,
the purpose and principle of the NAM still retains its practical
significance, and will lead the movement into the next century
with a fresh image, Zhu said. 
</P>
