<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 08:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Rejects Syrian Accusations of Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has rejected Syria's
accusations that it is seeking to form a military alliance with
Turkey and Israel against other Arab countries, a report of
the Jordan Times daily said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Syrian media can say what they want, but our stand is
clear. There is no way that Jordan will enter alliances that
target any Arab country," Jordanian Information Minister Nasir
Judeh told reporters late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
While admitting that Jordan and Turkey are carrying out
military cooperation, Judeh insisted that the move results from a
concern of "comprehensive security" of the region and is "for the
interests of all the Arab countries."
</P>
<P>
Syrian officials and the state-run media have criticized Jordan
for its relations with Turkey and Israel, which they said are
detrimental to Arab interests. Jordan is one of the only two Arab
countries after Egypt conceiving peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian official Al-Baath newspaper said on Sunday that
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz's current tour to Jordan and
Israel is "a hostile move Arab and Islamic countries should
confront."
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz ended a two-day visit to Jordan and traveled to Israel
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It is "wrong" to put the Jordanian-Turkish military cooperation
in the same ranks of the Turkish-Israeli relations, the Jordanian
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel signed a number of agreements in 1996 to
enhance cooperation in military and defense, a move which has met
with sharp criticism and strong opposition from Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries accuse Turkey, a predominately Muslim
country, of betraying the interests of the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Israel, a Jewish state, is occupying territories of Syria,
Lebanon and the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
