<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Combat Illegal Recruiters of Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
mounting a fresh crackdown on illegal recruiters following reports
of an international racket engaged in the slaughter and sale of
internal organs of overseas Filipino workers, Press Undersecretary
Lcasiano Gutierrez said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said President Joseph Estrada has ordered law enforcement
agencies and the Philippine Overseas Employment Administration as
well as the Overseas Workers Welfare Administration to make
aggressive efforts to unmask and bring to justice the illegal
recruiters and the alleged partners in the trade of human organs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Estrada ordered the concerned departments to launch
a massive information campaign in the provinces so that those
planning to seek employment abroad could be forewarned against
dealing with illegal recruiters, Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
"President Estrada considers illegal recruitment as a crime
more heinous than kidnapping because it victimizes the poor whose
dream to give their children a better life ultimately ends in
tragedy in foreign lands," Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
Gutierrez called on the people to support the government
campaigns by coming out and reporting any lead or information that
will help law enforcers track down and arrest these illegal
recruiters.
</P>
<P>
Families with kin working abroad should also bring to the
attention of the authorities any problem or apprehension confided
to them by their relatives, he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, presidential adviser on overseas workers affairs
William Gatchalian reported to the president that some Filipinos
working abroad were killed and their vital internal organs were
sold.
</P>
<P>
Gatchalian said members of the syndicate covered up their
crimes by passing off the death of their victims as suicide cases.
Many of the victims were also reported missing in their host
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
