<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Minister Urges Use of IT in Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Minister of
Education Arnaldo Nhavoto has called on the use of information
and telecommunication technologies in education in face of an
increasing population of pupils.
</P>
<P>
"Only by employing the information and telecommunication
technologies, can we satisfy the need of the rapidly increasing
population of pupils and train enough qualified teachers,"
Monday's Noticias newspaper quoted Nhavoto as saying recently.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a launching ceremony of the Project of Information
and Telecommunication Technologies in schools across the country,
the education minister said that the population of the pupils in
Form One to Form Four went from 1992's 1.2 million to 1.9 million
in 1998, up by 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the last three years, Nhavoto said, all school houses
damaged during the civil war were restored and the current number
of primary schools exceeds 3,110 in 1983.
</P>
<P>
In response to the rapid growth of the pupil population, he
disclosed, 12,000 teachers were recruited.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the fast expansion of primary schools has
brought a great challenge to the Mozambican educational system
and exerted a great pressure upon the higher education.
</P>
<P>
The development of education will be hindered by the
traditional modes of teaching and school construction, the
minister said, adding that television and radio stations will
play active roles in the education in the southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
Nhavoto also said that his ministry will conduct feasibility
study of the tele-educational system after a nationwide
discussion on policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
