<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Develop Huge Zinc Mine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- South African mining
giant, Anglo American Corporation (AAC) has announced that it
will develop a four-billion-Rand (660 million U.S. Dollars) zinc
mine in Northern Cape Province, producing 200,000 tons a year of
refined zinc.
</P>
<P>
The output of the future mine will be about four percent of
current Western world annual production, the Daily Business
quoted Anglo American Chairman Julian Ogilvie Thompson as
reporting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The development will create 2,000 jobs and be situated at
Northern Cape's Gamsberg deposit which contains about 90 million
tons of ore, grading at about 6.4 percent of zinc, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
The resources have been known for many years, but owing to a
troubled metallurgy, was never developed by Gold Fields of South
Africa, the mining house which agreed last Friday to sell its
controlling stake in the deposit to AAC.
</P>
<P>
AAC already had a 45 percent stake in Gamsberg.
</P>
<P>
Thompson said the mine would be a low-cast producer. AAC was
developing new technology which could yield even higher returns
from the investment, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
