<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Government Wins Confidence Vote in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand National
Party-led minority government won support from an expected
majority of the members of the Parliament in a confidence vote
here Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The confidence vote in the House was taken according to Prime
Minister Jenny Shipley's proposal. This was the first time in New
Zealand's history that a government initiated a confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
Observers here were of the view that through this test, Shipley
wants to establish political stability as economic recession in
the country deepens.
</P>
<P>
In the 120-seat Parliament, 62 voted for the cabinet that was
set up a week ago after the collapse of the coalition government
formed by the National Party and New Zealand First.
</P>
<P>
The votes in favor came from such disparate quarters as the
National Party's 44 MPs, ACT New Zealand's eight MPs, the eight
New Zealand First defectors, United New Zealand leader Peter Dunne
and independent MP Alamein Kopu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
