<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Ugandan Kids Immunized: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Most of Ugandan kids have
been immunized in the first round of the 1998 National
Immunization Days (NIDs) for polio eradication which was
successfully conducted in early August, a report has said.
</P>
<P>
The report, carried in Tuesday's New Vision daily, was issued
by the Ugandan Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
It said a total of 3,962,701 kids, or 97.7 percent of all
Ugandan children under the age of five years have received
immunization across the east African country.
</P>
<P>
The districts of Sembabule, Ntungamo and Rakai had the lowest
coverage of less than 50 percent while other districts have
continued to perform very well.
</P>
<P>
The report attributes the poor turn-up in some areas to
widespread rumors and misconceptions about NIDs and lack of
adequate information and explanation.
</P>
<P>
The association of NIDs Oral Polio vaccine with recent malaria
outbreaks in western and southwestern Uganda adversely affected
the turn-up of children during the immunization campaign,
especially in the districts of Ntungamo, Mbarara, Rakai,
Sembabule and Bushenyi.
</P>
<P>
The health ministry thanked all those who had helped the
successful implementation of NIDs and announced the second round
is scheduled to take place on September 12 to 13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
