<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Economy Forecast to Shrink This year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Treasurer Bill
Birch submitted a Treasury Forecast to the Parliament Tuesday,
announcing that the economy of the country is to shrink this year
for the first time since 1992.
</P>
<P>
According to the forecast, the New Zealand Government will
cling to a surplus of 100 million New Zealand dollars (about 50
million U.S. dollars) this fiscal year, but the economy is
expected to contract 0.5 percent in the year ending March 1999.
This would trim tax revenues and plunge government accounts into
the red in the next two fiscal years.
</P>
<P>
Though the Treasury painted a gloomy picture for the short
term, it held out hope for an economic recovery next year. In its
forecast, the Treasury said that the economic growth of New
Zealand is expected to be 2.9 percent in 1999-2000 and 4 percent
in 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury said that market volatility, lower business and
consumer confidence, drought, and the Asian crisis prompted it to
revise its 1998-1999 forecast of 2.7 percent economic growth made
in the May 14 Budget.
</P>
<P>
Lower growth is expected to trim the surplus, estimated at 1.2
billion New Zealand dollars (about 600 million U.S. dollars) in
the budget, to 100 million New Zealand dollars this year.
Afterwards, the surpluses run since 1994 will disappear. The
Treasury forecasts a deficit of 700 million New Zealand dollars
(about 350 million U.S. dollars) in 1999-2000 and 300 million New
Zealand dollars (about 150 million U.S. dollars) the year after.
</P>
<P>
According to the Treasury Forecast, the unemployment rate in
New Zealand is expected to rise to 8.5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Birch said that despite the downturn, "the New Zealand economy
has shown great resilience and an ability to bounce back."
</P>
<P>
Bearing in mind that Asia, which took 40 percent of New
Zealand's exports last year, has suffered massive economic losses,
today's release was "a pretty good forecast," he said.
</P>
<P>
Reforms of the past 15 years meant New Zealand was better
placed to cope with global shocks, such as the Asia crisis, than
previously, Birch said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that U.S. ratings agency Moody's looks almost
certain to downgrade New Zealand's foreign currency debt rating
following today's gloomy economic outlook from the Treasury.
</P>
</TEXT>
