<HEADLINE> Five Students Injured in Clash With Police in Jakarta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- At least five students were
reportedly injured in a clash between students and security forces
at dawn here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The clash broke out when the security officers, mostly from the
police and the marines, tried to evict the demonstrators by firing
teargas canisters at them, prompting the students to retaliate
with stones and bottles.
</P>
<P>
Two students sustained wounds from bayonets and the other three
were either hit by stones or were trampled upon in the incident,
according to Antara News Agency reports.
</P>
<P>
About 1,500 students staging a rally at the House of
Representatives (DPR) building here since Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Following the clash, the students decided to march to the
University of Atmajaya, some two kilometers from the DPR, but
threatened to return Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The DPR compound was finally cleared of protesters by 3:20
a.m., but troops began blockading the streets leading to the
building.
</P>
<P>
The students were protesting the spiraling prices of the basic
commodities and were calling for the resignation of President B.J.
Habibie.
</P>
<P>
In the country's second largest city of Surabaya, thousands of
students from 26 universities and colleges Tuesday also staged a
demonstration, calling the government to curb the skyrocketing
prices of basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
Over the past couple of weeks, rice prices have sharply
increased to about 5,000 rupiah (0.45 U.S. dollars) per kilogram,
compared to the Indonesian government target price of 2,000 rupiah
per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
The government has accused hoarders and smugglers of causing
the sharp increase in the price. 
</P>
</TEXT>
