<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 08:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Literacy Rate up to 90 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's literacy rate rose to
90 percent by the end of 1997, thanks to the continuous efforts in
school education and adult education, according to an official
statement obtained here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement was released by the Ministry of Education to mark
the International Literacy Day on September 9.
</P>
<P>
It said Jordan's achievement is encouraging in view of a 32.3
percent literacy rate in the kingdom in 1966 when adult education
was introduced, and an average 49 percent literacy rate in the
whole Arab world in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's establishment of schools across the kingdom and
its efforts to improve the quality of education have achieved a
school attendance rate of 98 percent among the children in the
1996-1997 school year, thus helping improve the literacy rate.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's measure starting in 1997 to make education
compulsory until 10th grade also helped achieve a high literacy
rate, the statement added. In 1964, Jordan made education
compulsory until ninth grade, a stipulation that stayed for 33
years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement added, the ministry's efforts to
popularize education among illiterate adults also helped push up
the literacy rate. It has offered education classes to a total of
350,000 illiterate adults since the program started in 1966.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, with a 4.6-million population, had 2,800 government-run
schools, some 950 private schools, 55 community colleges, six
state-run universities and six private universities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
