<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Expects 30 Percent Drop in Sales in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Coca-Cola Company expects a 30
percent fall in sales in Zambia following its price hike by 80
percent in the local market effective Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Post Tuesday quoted Ian Ackerman, general manager of
Zambia Bottlers Limited, Coca-Cola's manufacturer in Zambia, as
saying Monday that his company expected sales to fall by 30
percent after it raised the price from 500 Kwacha (one U.S.
dollar equals 2000 Kwacha) to 900 Kwacha each bottle.
</P>
<P>
The price hike came after the Zambian government's failure to
honor the agreement reached in May with Coca-Cola under which it
will reduce the company's excise duty from 25 percent to five
percent while Coca-Cola in turn pledged to invest 75 million
dollars in the country.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola declared last Thursday that it would raise the
prices for soft drinks, suspend its investment program and scale
down its operations in Zambia. It also said that reluctance of
the Zambian government to honor the agreement will also
facilitate the company's departure from this country.
</P>
<P>
According to Ackerman, his company will scale down its
production with effect from Tuesday and it has now engaged a
"wait and see" attitude towards the government before it takes
further action.
</P>
<P>
Local vendors complained that their daily sales of Coca-Cola's
soft drinks dropped massively Monday due to the price hike.
</P>
<P>
And Zambia Congress of Trade Unions on the same day urged the
Zambian government to honor its agreement with Coca-Cola, warning
that if the agreement was abandoned, there would be 15,000
Zambians to lose their jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
