<P>
KAMPALA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of supporters of
Kampala Mayor Nasser Sebaggala in Uganda have petitioned the U.S.
government to have him released pending his trial.
</P>
<P>
Some 24,000 people have signed and more are expected, Godfrey
Ntale, the mayor's publicity and research officer, was quoted by
Tuesday's New Vision daily as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The appeal, which was addressed to U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, will be in the U.S. via U.S. Ambassador to
Uganda Nancy Powell.
</P>
<P>
The petition asked the U.S. to grant the mayor bail to enable
him to answer the charges while executing his duties as mayor of
the Ugandan capital.
</P>
<P>
It said that Sebaggala is trustworthy and has never had any
criminal record. That is why he was elected Mayor of Kampala in
April this year.
</P>
<P>
The mayor was arrested on June 13 in the U.S. over bank fraud
and making false statements to customs officers. He will face 30
years' imprisonment if convicted.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan police said that he also faces the same charges even
back at home.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most of his opponents have demanded him down from
the mayoral post because he does not have A level certificate as
required by the post. 
</P>
