<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Central Bank Chief Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Central Bank President
Sergei Dubinin offered his resignation Monday and went on leave
while his appeal is being considered, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Dubinin's post now is taken over by Deputy Finance Minister
Sergei Aleksashenko until a new head is appointed.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the president, Dubinin said that he had found it
"practically impossible" to work amid demands by both the Duma
(lower house of parliament) and acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
Dubinin, along with former prime minister Sergei Kiriyenko, had
offered his resignation immediately after the ruble devaluation
was announced last month. But President Boris Yeltsin had then
refused to accept.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time that Dubinin was losing a government
post because of a fall in the ruble's value. He was sacked as
deputy finance minister after the ruble's 21 percent fall on the
so-called Black Tuesday of October 1994.
</P>
<P>
Aleksashenko, who accounted the Dubinin's resignation to the
absence of political support for the bank's operations, said that
he will continue the bank policy, as he does not have any
extraordinary plan, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
