<HEADLINE> Afghan President Seeks Turkey's Support in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Ousted Afghan President
Burhanuddin Rabbani has asked Turkey to support his Northern
Alliance in fighting against Taliban, Turkey's Daily News reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani's alliance controlling a slice of northern Afghanistan
suffered a serious setback last month when the Taliban captured
Mazari Sharif, a stronghold of the alliance in the north.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani was driven out of the capital Kabul in 1996 by the
Taliban, which is controlling more than 85 percent of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview here with the newspaper, Rabbani said
that external forces were provoking the situation in his country.
</P>
<P>
"We are victims of external interference. If this stops, the
crisis (in Afghanistan) will disappear," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting after arriving here Sunday for an unexpected
visit, Rabbani briefed Turkish President Suleyman Demirel on the
recent developments in his war-torn country, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Demirel as saying that the Afghan crisis will
only be solved through broad-based peace talks aimed at national
unity, not by military means.
</P>
<P>
In another meeting, Turkish State Minister Ahat Andican told
Rabbani that regional countries, including Turkey, would put more
pressure on Pakistan to refrain from supporting the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Andican disclosed that Demirel would hold talks with Pakistani
leaders on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
