<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tailor-Made Food May Be Order of Future: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Tailor-made foods made to fit
personal dietary plans aimed at allowing consumers to maintain
their health may well be the order of the future, according to an
Australian nutrition expert.
</P>
<P>
Katrine Baghurst, manager of human nutrition's consumer science
of Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research
Organization (CSIRO), said future food trends would be influenced
by consumers starved of time rather than food, with increased
demand for food that met a busy lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
She predicted the evolution of foods based on individual
dietary plans which take into account a person's genetic
predisposition to a range of dietary-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
"As medical technology allows people to genetically map the
diseases to which they may be prone, they will be able to develop
a personal health profile and dietary plan which best suits their
needs," she told the Australian Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
"In future years, when we have a better idea of our personal
susceptibility to a condition, we may be able to choose from a
line of foods developed by manufacturers which are suitable for
those with certain conditions."
</P>
<P>
Baghurst will talk about what people will choose to eat in the
future at the CSIRO Human Nutrition's 12th annual food conference
in the southern Australian city of Adelaide, which begins
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speakers from around the world will discuss topics including
foods for cancer protection, trends in health and disease and
foods which influence mood and the immune system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
