<HEADLINE> World-Class Gold Mines to be Found in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australia-based Broken
Hill Proprietary Co. Ltd. (BHP) has signed a contract with
southwest China's Guizhou Province to jointly seek gold deposits
in the province's Nanpan River Valley over the next six years.
</P>
<P>
The venture expects to discover gold mines with reserves
exceeding 100 tons in the area, according to Sergvei Diatchkov,
manager of the company's prospecting department.
</P>
<P>
A new gold production base, Guizhou has witnessed a rapid
growth of gold output since 1987 when it began goldmining, and
output achieved a year-to-year increase of 35.7 percent during
1991-1995.
</P>
<P>
So far, some 300 tons of gold deposits have been found in the
province's Buyi-Miao Autonomous Prefecture, where the cooperative
exploration will begin.
</P>
<P>
Under the six-year contract, the firm will invest six million
U.S. dollars in the first phase of prospecting, the biggest
investment China has ever attracted for gold prospecting, said Deng
Shaoqing, a senior official with the provincial geology and mining
company.
</P>
<P>
The Carlin-type gold mines to be explored in the autonomous
prefecture are of the low-grade and metallurgical refactory type,
prospecting for which was opened to foreign companies in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The company has promised to apply the latest exploring theories
and technologies to this undertaking.
</P>
<P>
The Nanning-Kunming Railway which runs across the region has
was completed recently, with a 2.52-million-kw hydropower station
under construction nearby. A program-controlled telephone system
has also begun operating in the area.
</P>
<P>
More foreign firms have shown interest in the district's gold
mines as the investment environment continues to improve, said
Deng.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
