<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Should Further Open Its Service Sector: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China will not become an
economic giant unless it further opens its service sector and
speeds up foreign service trade.
</P>
<P>
This is the consensus reached by a group of experts attending a
symposium on the growth of China's service sector recently in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to these experts, the service sector covers a host of
industries such as traffic, transportation, telecommunications
finance, trade, education, scientific research, tourism, real
estate, service for production and service for daily life.
</P>
<P>
Long Yongtu, vice-minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation, said China will never make top world achievements if
it does not open its service sector to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China should open up its post and
telecommunications industry step by step. "The storage capacity of
China's basic telecommunications network ranks second in the
world. However, income from this sector is far less than some
foreign countries."
</P>
<P>
Researcher Dr. Zhang Xiaoji agreed with Long, saying that China
should speed up its pace in this regard. At present, he noted,
the total world output value of the posts and telecommunications
industry has exceeded one trillion U.S. dollars, and trade volume
in this sector (including services and equipment) has surpassed
100 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said that China, by so doing, can import new products
and advanced services, reduce costs through competition and
attract foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
Regarding some worries that the country could lose control of
the industry and safety concerns, Zhang said that China, as a
sovereign state, can standardize the activities of foreign
companies according to laws, and punish those who violate related
laws and damage the interests and threaten the safety of China
in accordance with laws.
</P>
<P>
Some experts also suggested that China can introduce foreign
funds into its retail sector, in a bid to develop its commercial
circulation system in a way more adaptable to international
practice.
</P>
<P>
China has made some achievements in the opening of its service
sector. Its export volume ranked the 16th in the world in 1997
compared with 27th in 1992; total earnings from tourism was 12
billion U.S. dollars in 1997, 27 times that of 1979; and by the
end of 1997, the country had approved 73,658 foreign-funded
programs in the service sector, involving 207.69 billion
U.S. dollars in foreign investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
