<HEADLINE> Southwestern Yunnan Province to Expand Coffee Growing Acreage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
Province will add 3,133 hectares annually to its existing
coffee-growing area within the next three years.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, by the year 2000 the coffee-growing
area in Yunnan province will total 16,666 hectares producing
15,000 tons of dried coffee beans annually.
</P>
<P>
About 420 million yuan (50 million US dollars) of investment
will be needed to realize this plan, and local governments at
various levels in the province will also investment in water
improving control facilities in coffee-growing regions.
</P>
<P>
Many areas of Yunnan are tropical and subtropical, providing
suitable natural conditions for growing small coffee beans.
</P>
<P>
The province, first in China in the production and processing
of coffee beans, now sows 7,333 hectares of coffee and produces
3,500 tons of dried coffee beans annually.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the International Coffee Organization say that
small coffee beans grown in Yunnan are nearly the equal of the
well-known Columbia coffee beans in quality.
</P>
<P>
The coffee giants Maxwell and Nestle companies have both signed
contracts with Yunnan to provide them with 10,000 tons of beans by
the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
China now consumes approximately 10,000 tons of coffee beans a
year, 70 percent of which are imported. This number is expected
to rise to 20,000 tons by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
While working out a plan for developing its coffee industry,
the Yunnan Provincial Government has decided to set up a center
for coffee research and related processing technology.
Preparations have been made to open a coffee bean-trading market,
said local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
