<HEADLINE> Lebanon Sees Evil Behind Turkish-Israeli Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister
Farez Boueiz has accused Turkey and Israel of plotting against
their Arab neighbors, citing their increasing military and
economic cooperation, the Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We're very worried about what's happening despite Turkey's
repeated claims that its relations with Israel do not go further
than training and technical cooperation," Boueiz said.
</P>
<P>
"We see the alliance like a pair of pliers closing in on Arab
states that refuse to make peace with Israel, particularly Lebanon
and Syria," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "No one can be convinced that this cooperation is
merely for training."
</P>
<P>
Boueiz's comments coincided with a visit by Turkish Prime
Minister Mesut Yilmaz to Israel and Jordan. At a news conference,
Yilmaz and his Israeli counterpart Benjamin Netanyahu described as
"baseless" Lebanese and Syrian fears.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a predominantly Muslim but politically secular country,
has signed two military cooperation agreements with Israel since
1996. It allows Israeli jets to use its airspace for training
while Israel agrees to upgrade Turkey's F-4 fighters under a
contract worth 630 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The growing Israeli relations with Turkey as well as Jordan
have sparked harsh criticism and fears from most Arab countries,
especially Syria and Lebanon, whose Golan Heights and south
Lebanon respectively are still under Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
They feared that the three countries will form a military
alliance and threaten the security and interests of other Arab
countries in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
