<HEADLINE> Sam Rainsy Leaves Hotel While Demonstration Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Sam Rainsy, the main
opposition leader left the Cambodiana Hotel where he took refuge
while protests against the Second Prime Minister Hun Sen continued
on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy left the hotel under the protection of UN officials
at about 10:30 am local time, and went straight to another
opposition leader, Prince Ranariddh's residence.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of opposition supporters, including monks and college
students again gathered outside the National Assembly to continue
the sit-in, which began on August 24.
</P>
<P>
The decision to arrest Sam Rainsy has put off temporarily after
Mehrotra, the UN Secretary General's representative in Cambodia
consulted with Hun Sen and the Co-Minister of Interior Sar Kheng.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen issued the arrest warrant for Sam Rainsy Monday after
Hun Sen's Phnom Penh house was attacked by three grenades.
</P>
<P>
The government accused Sam Rainsy and other opposition leaders
of assassinating Hun Sen in order to bring down the legitimate
government and to create a political crisis.
</P>
<P>
The statement broadcast on state-owned TV of Cambodia also
accused opposition leaders, especially Sam Rainsy of turning
democracy into a movement instigating violence, anarchy and
splitting the nation.
</P>
<P>
One person was killed and several others wounded Monday evening
as police opened fire to disperse demonstrators who gathered
outside the Cambodiana Hotel to chant support for Sam Rainsy.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday Hun Sen said the protest outside the National
Assembly must end by midnight. But most of the protesters
ignored the order to leave.
</P>
<P>
The two main opposition political parties of Funcinpec and the
Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) rejected the election result which Hun
Sen's Cambodia People's Party won 64 of the 122 parliament seats.
</P>
<P>
They organized a month-long demonstration and two-week sit-in
in front of the National Assembly boycotting the new government
and demanding Second Prime Minister Hun Sen step down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
