<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Urban Population Exceeds 10 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's urban population
now exceeds 10 million with the expansion of its urban area.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that permanent Shanghai residents
including the city's suburbs has reached 13.05 million, with 10.67
of these urban residents.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the city's urban population was less than 8 million.
</P>
<P>
The rise in the city's urban population is attributed to three
urban area expansion projects over recent years. In 1993, the
Pudong New Area was added to the city and the Jiading and Minhang
districts were included in Shanghai's urban districts; in 1997,
the city turned Jinshan county into its Jinshan district, and this
year, the city's Songjiang county was made a district.
</P>
<P>
These three projects added 2.58 million to the city's total
urban population.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, population in the city's downtown area has
decreased rapidly because of the transformation of urban
life. Huangpu District, for example, has seen its population drop
to 56,000 per square kilometer from more than 70,000 in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Income Inequality Between Poor, Rich Widens in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A study released Monday
shows that income inequality between the poor and rich in the
United States has widened since 1989.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by the Economic Policy Institute, said the
very lowest-wage workers saw their earnings had risen only by 1.4
percent between 1989-1997, while the executives' pay had more than
doubled during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Working families in the 1990s have faced increased working
hours, stagnant or falling incomes, and less secure jobs offering
fewer benefits, which have all contributed to inequality in wages
and family income compared to the richest families, said Jared
Bernstein, an economist at the Economic Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
The typical married-couple working family in U.S. worked 247
more hours -- an additional six weeks annually -- in 1996 than in
1989 in order to boost their incomes, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the richest 10 percent of households in the United
States have reaped 85.8 percent of growth in the stock market
since 1989, the study said, pointing out the average pay for the
executives jumped 116 times that of workers.
</P>
<P>
The study suggests the record profitability of U.S. companies
in the 1990s has come partly at the expense of their workers.
</P>
<P>
"Had profitability grown at historically normal levels, hourly
compensation could have been seven percent higher in 1997 than it
actually was," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0211 </DOCNO>
