<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislative Inspections to Promote Integration of Science, Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- To promote the integration of
scientific research and economic growth and stimulate enterprises
to invest more in technological innovation, China's top
legislature will start inspection tours tomorrow to see how a
science law is being enforced in the country.
</P>
<P>
The legislature has spent two days examining reports by eight
ministerial-level government bodies on how they have been
implementing the 1996 law on promoting the conversion of
scientific and technological results. These government bodies
include the Ministry of Science and Technology and the Chinese
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Peng Peiyun, vice-chairperson of the National People's Congress
(NPC) Standing Committee, said at the meeting that "it must be
clearly realized that, in general, problems in integrating
scientific research and economic growth have yet to be solved;
only a small proportion of research findings are commercialized or
put into industrial production; and manufacturers and other
enterprises are lax in technological explorations."
</P>
<P>
"China's conversion rate of technologies into productivity and
the contribution of scientific research are rather low as compared
with developed countries," she said.
</P>
<P>
The top legislature expects that this law enforcement
inspection will prompt local governments to increase their efforts
to provide favorable policy guidelines and invest more in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
The inspection tours will be headed by Peng and Zhou Guangzhao,
vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, and cover Beijing,
Shaanxi Province and Shanghai. All other provinces, municipalities
and autonomous regions will be inspected by their local
legislatures.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Science and Technology said that lack of
funds has stalled the conversion of scientific results into
productivity.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, statistics show that the annual input for research
and technological exploration in China in the past four years
accounts for only 0.5 percent of the value of Gross Domestic
Production (GDP), while the rates in developed countries range
from two to three percent.
</P>
<P>
The central government plans to invest 1.5 percent of the
GDP value in scientific research by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"This goal will hardly be reached unless prompt, drastic
measures are taken right now," the ministry said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
