<HEADLINE> Chinese Port City To Upgrade Highways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Qingdao, a major port city in
east China's Shandong Province, plans to invest 10 billion yuan in
highways over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
By year 2002, the city will have set up a modern highway
network, eight years ahead of the national schedule, with several
expressways linking all the surrounding cities and the national
highway network, a city communications department official said.
</P>
<P>
The plan includes the Qingdao section of a national expressway
along the east coast of China and an expressway running from Qingdao
to Yinchuan, capital of the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region in
northwest China. Construction of the two expressways will begin
this year.
</P>
<P>
The city will also build highways to all of its villages.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao Port, the country's largest crude oil depot and the
second largest container shipping port, now has an annual handling
capacity of 84.3 million tons of cargo. Local experts believe
that construction of the new highways will help the port play a
bigger role in promoting the local economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
