<HEADLINE> Iron Oxen Replacing Yaks in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Tractors, known as iron oxen in
China's countryside, can now be found rushing from one end to the
other over farmland on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, leaving yaks,
which used to play a vital role in gathering local crops, idle at
home.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics from Tibet show there are now nine
trucks, six tractors and three shellers for every 100 families;
and more seeders and winnowers are also appearing on the
snow-covered land.
</P>
<P>
Fixed production assets held by each household are now valued
at 8,000 yuan, a huge rise from five years ago, according to these
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, agricultural machinery is one of the most popular
items on the Tibetan market.
</P>
<P>
"The sales volume for my company is expected to reach 10
million yuan (1.2 million US dollars)," a young manager said
contentedly. He used to be a farmer, but three years ago he opened
a company in Shigatse selling agricultural machinery.
</P>
<P>
Tibet replaced the traditional wooden plough with iron ploughs
in the 1960s. Ten years later, farmers there greeted the first
tractor to enter Lhasa with a grand ceremony, as if it were a
distinguished bride. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
