<HEADLINE> China to Open "Shangri-la Air Route" in Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Tourists will be able to
realize their dream of a trip to Shangri-La when the Diqing
Airport in southwest China's Yunnan Province opens in next June.
</P>
<P>
Shangri-la, as described in British writer James Hilton's
classic 1930s novel "Lost Horizon," was a peaceful, quiet, and
beautiful land in which human beings lived in harmony with nature.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, a team of Chinese experts reached the conclusion that
Shangri-la was actually located in the Diqing Tibetan Autonomous
Prefecture in Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
Despite the difficulties of travel, over 300,000 tourists were
attracted to this mysterious and beautiful mecca in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Liu Ping, director of the Tourism Bureau of Yunnan said that
at the cost of 250 million yuan construction of the Diqing
Airport began in this past January. Upon completion next June,
an air route to this Shangri-la will be opened.
</P>
<P>
Diqing is located at the juncture of Yunnan and Sichuan
provinces, and the Tibet Autonomous Region. It is known for
its pyramid-like snow-covered mountain ridges and peaks, steep
valleys, luxuriant grasslands and majestic temples.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
