<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia's Public Finances Hit Troubled Waters: Acting PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia is having serious
problems with its public finance in the wake of domestic political
turmoil and the financial crisis in east Asia and Russia, acting
Prime Minister Tsakhiya Elbegdorj said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with People's Rights daily, he said initial
estimates put this year's revenue 10 billion togrog (117.6 million
U.S. dollars) lower than the budget figure, forcing the state to
postpone investments of six billion togrog (70.6 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Elbegdorj, whose three-month old coalition government was
dismissed on July 24 after losing a vote of confidence in the
parliament, said grave socio-economic troubles were piling up in
the long-time vacancy of the supreme executive power.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition, the president and the parliament are
locked in disagreement on the nomination of a new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ongoing financial crisis in east Asia and the
worsening economic crisis in Russia are having a direct impact on
Mongolia's social and economic life, said the acting prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Bank, the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund have suspended planned aid totalling 45 million dollars to
Mongolia, which was already included in its budget.
</P>
<P>
The suspension followed the split of the state-owned Renovation
Bank and the private Golomt Bank which had merged in May.
</P>
<P>
To ease the emerging financial crisis, the parliament has
lately approved the issue of 20-billion-togrog (235.3 million
dollars) worth of state bonds this year.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia has recorded a significant reduction in the volume of
its foreign trade in the first six months of this year, with a
deficit of 89.8 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The rapid shrinking of the country's foreign exchange reserve,
from 120 million dollars in January to 75.7 million dollars in
June, has led the Mongolian currency on a steady slide against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia's budget deficit in the first half of this year
amounted to 27.2 billion togrog (320 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
