<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls Outside Trade More Important for Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The share of extraregional
trade will increase significantly in Asia over the next few year,
Adrianus Mooy, secretary of the U.N. Economic and Social
Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) said at a seminar here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, titled "Emerging Trade and Investment Scenarios
and Liberalization Agenda for Asia and the Pacific" and opened
Monday, aims to address the effects of the Asian crisis on trade
and investment flows, options available for policy makers within
and outside the region and the likely short-, medium- and
long-term trade and investment scenarios.
</P>
<P>
Mooy said one of the major impacts of the Asian Crisis is
likely to be on intraregional trade, whose growth during the past
decade had been an important component of the Asian success story.
</P>
<P>
However, the region can no longer count on itself as a robust
market for exports. That's why extraregional trade will become
more important for Asia, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mooy also said most of the studies and meetings on the Asian
crisis so far have focused on the origins of the crisis and means
to solve it.
</P>
<P>
"What has been largely ignored in current economic analysis,
bailout packages and policy initiatives relates to microeconomic
aspects of the crisis, such as trade and investment policies," he
said.
</P>
<P>
This was a glaring omission as the Asian economic model has
been predicated on strong trade growth and inward-flows of foreign
direct investment for most countries, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
