<HEADLINE> Sampras Coasts into U.S. Open Quarterfinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Pete Sampras gave
talented Russian teenager Marat Safin a straight-set clinic today
and moved into the quarterfinals on a rainy day at the U.S. Open
tennis championships here today.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old Safin was stunned by Sampras' powerful serves
and lost the match 4-6, 3-6, 2-6. Sampras fired 18 aces,
including three in a row to end the match, and faced only two
break points in the 77-minute battle that was delayed by rain for
more than two hours early in the second set.
</P>
<P>
Sampras will face the winner of the fourth round match between
the eighth seed American Andre Agassi or Karol Kucera of Slovakia
in the quarterfinals. Kucera was leading 6-3, 6-3, 6-7 (5-7), 0-3
before rain suspended play for the day.
</P>
<P>
Two other men's matches fell victim to the rain and, along
with the Agassi-Kucera match, have been rescheduled for Tuesday's
day session.
</P>
<P>
Third seed and defending champion Patrick Rafter of Australia
was leading 14th seed Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia 6-3, 3-2, and
number 12 Jonas Bjorkman of Sweden held a 6-4, 1-4 lead over Jan
Siemerink of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Among the women, second seed Lindsay Davenport of the United
States, in searching of her Grand Slam singles title and the No.
1 ranking, stormed past 10th seed Nathalie Tauziat of France 6-1,
6-4.
</P>
<P>
Fourth seed Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain earned her first
victory in four meetings with Russian teenager Anna
Kournikova,upending the 15th seed 7-6 (7-5), 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Also, fifth seed Venus Williams of the United States fought
off number 12 Mary Pierce of France 6-1, 7-6 (7-4), and number 13
Amanda Coetzer of South Africa outlasted seventh seed Conchita
Martinez of Spain 6-4, 4-6, 6-2 in a two hour, 38-minute marathon.
</P>
<P>
Davenport will face Coetzer in the quarterfinals, and
Williams, who lost to Hingis in last year's final, will play
Sanchez Vicario.
</P>
<P>
Kucera seemed ready to close out Agassi after going up a break
in the second game of the third set, but Agassi broke back in the
seventh game on a crosscourt backhand winner. After some spirited
gamesmanship between the two and a bizarre lobbing strategy
employed by Agassi in the ninth game, both players held serve to
force the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
Agassi stormed ahead to a 4-0 lead in the tiebreak, but Kucera
won the next five points. However, Agassi managed to win the next
three points to take the set.
</P>
<P>
Davenport needed just over an hour to reach her second
straight U.S. Open quarterfinals. She broke Tauziat five times
and won 68 points to Tauziat's 50 as she avenged a quarterfinal
loss at Wimbledon. Tauziat had 25 unforced errors and was
successful on only 48 percent of her first serves.
</P>
<P>
Williams dominated the opening set but Pierce made a match of
it after the rain delay. At 5-5 in the second set, Williams and
Pierce battled through nine deuce points before Williams broke
serve and served for the set.
</P>
<P>
Pierce broke back, sending the set to the tiebreak, and
appeared ready to take it when she built a 4-1 lead. But Williams
reeled off six consecutive points to take the tiebreak and the
match. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
