<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Steps Up Education Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is implementing a
national plan of action for education for all with added momentum
and experience gained from the last literacy campaign between
1964 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
The plan, laid down by the World Education Conference on
Education for All held in Thailand in 1990, covers both formal and
non-formal education.
</P>
<P>
Formal education is designed to enable school-age children from
five to nine to go to school and primary school children to
complete primary education.
</P>
<P>
Non-formal education is aimed at enabling illiterates over
school age (over 15) to become literate by means of the
"functional literacy program."
</P>
<P>
The two education programs aim to ensure that 80 percent of the
population complete primary education and to reduce the adult
illiteracy rate from 22 percent to 11 percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
A total of 180,035 persons are attending classes in 104
townships under the non-formal education program in the country.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's literacy campaign started in 1964. In 20 years, the
illiteracy rate of the country was reduced by half to only 21
percent in 1983 from 43 percent in 1963.
</P>
<P>
Between 1964 and 1988, 490,398 volunteers took part in literacy
activities with more than 2.4 million illiterates becoming
literate.
</P>
<P>
The literacy rate of women has gone up to 71.3 percent in the
past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has been awarded two international prizes for its
successful literacy activities by the U.N. Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Organization.
</P>
<P>
They are the Mahammad Reza Pahlavi Literacy Prize in 1971 and
the Noma Prize in 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Host Next NAM Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will host the next
summit of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) scheduled for 2001, press
reports here said Tuesday.
</P>
