<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Impose Limit on Presidential Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The five factions of the
People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), Indonesia's highest
legislative body, have agreed to impose a limit on the
presidential term, the Jakarta Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Team of Assistants to the body's working committee said
here Monday that the factions agreed that the special MPR session
planned for November should impose a limitation on the
presidential term and abolish the president's extraordinary power
granted by the last session in March this year.
</P>
<P>
The presidential term limitation proposal was made amid growing
public calls for the MPR to act in this field as the 1945
constitution has been criticized for being "too vague" in
regulating the issue.
</P>
<P>
The constitution's Article VII only states that the country's
president could be "elected again" after his or her first term,
without citing how many times.
</P>
<P>
The extraordinary power that the team referred to was granted
by the controversial MPR Decree No. V/1998 that gives the
president the right to take preemptive security measures "to
safeguard the development and the state ideology Pancasila."
</P>
<P>
Pancasila is the five basic principles of the Republic of
Indonesia, including the belief in the one and only God Almighty,
humanity that is just and civilized, the unity of Indonesia,
democracy guided by the wisdom of representative deliberation and
social justice for all Indonesians.
</P>
<P>
Tosari Wijaya, a member of the Team of Assistants, said the
proposal agreed by the team would be debated again during the
upcoming meeting of the working committee, which is preparing the
agenda for the upcoming November 10-14 MPR special session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Set to Reap Near Record Wheat Crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Australian farmers are set to
reap a near record wheat crop this financial year, thanks to good
growing conditions, Australia's chief official commodity
forecaster said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a significant revision, the latest crop report of the
Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics estimates
that the wheat crop for the 1998-1999 financial year will hit 23.5
million tons, 4.2 million tons higher than its previous forecast.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents an increase of 26 percent over last year
and is close to the 1996-1997 record of 23.7 million tons, the
bureau's Executive Director Brian Fisher said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Excellent growing conditions in most regions are expected to
lead to above-average yields for this financial year, which ends
on June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
But Fisher noted that spring weather would play a big role in
determining the final yields and grain quality as extra rain
expected in eastern states following the El Nino effect's
departure raises the risk of further crop damage from waterlogging
and plant diseases.
</P>
<P>
The bureau expects the area planted with wheat to rise to about
11.8 million hectares in the current financial year from 11.1
million hectares.
</P>
<P>
"This increase in area is driven largely by a reduction in
sheep numbers, reflecting the pessimistic outlook for wool prices
and the expected favorable returns for wheat relative to other
crops," it said.
</P>
<P>
Despite flood damage to some crops in New South Wales State and
southern Queensland State, two major grain producers in the
nation, Australia is on track to achieve the second highest winter
crop production on record of about 35 million tons, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
