<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Supreme Court Drops Case Against Three MPs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of Thailand
has dismissed a lawsuit against three members of parliament about
election fraud, thus defusing a crisis threatening the coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
The ruling means that the government under Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai retains its 23-MP slim majority in the 389-seat House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Handing down its verdict late Monday, the court said however
that there had been fraud in Samut Prakan's Constituency 1 on
November 17, 1996, involving current Deputy Interior Minister
Vatana Assavahame and two other Prachakorn Thai Party MPs.
</P>
<P>
The opposition has alleged that the three MPs were engaged in
"fraudulent deals" at several polling stations and asked the court
to declare the vote invalid and order a new election.
</P>
<P>
But the court said the constitution, enforced since October 11
last year, states that the three accused MPs' status would be
terminated only at the end of the lower house's four-year term.
</P>
<P>
The constitution also bans new elections to vacant seats in the
lower house. "Even though irregularities may have been involved, a
new election cannot be called," the court said.
</P>
<P>
The Election Act also states that if a new election cannot be
held, a suit challenging election results has to be dropped.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing the case, the Supreme Court said that since a new
election can not be held, there is no need to consider the alleged
fraudulent deals in the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Review Rice, Debt Issues With Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) will focus this month's review of Indonesia's reform
program on lowering the price of rice and settling domestic debt
of local corporations.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting with Indonesian senior economic ministers
here Monday, IMF Asia Pacific director Hubert Neiss said the
current price of rice is too high and actions have to be taken to
correct the problem.
</P>
<P>
"The rice subsidies will stay as long as necessary because rice
is the people's basic need," he was quoted as saying by newspapers
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the government must limit the subsidies to
the poor.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has allocated more than 15 trillion
rupiah (about 1.4 billion U.S. dollars) in the current fiscal
year, which will end in March 1999, to finance the subsidy for the
staple.
</P>
<P>
Over the past couple of weeks, rice prices have sharply
increased to about 5,000 rupiah (45 U.S. cents) per kilogram,
compared with the Indonesian government's target price of 2,000
rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The government has accused hoarders and smugglers of causing
the sharp increase in the price.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of students staged a major demonstration on Monday at
the House of Representatives (DPR) building, protesting the high
price of rice and demanding that President B. J. Habibie step
down.
</P>
<P>
Neiss arrived here on Sunday for the monthly review of the
IMF-sponsored economic reform program, a precondition for the
disbursement of the agency's 43 billion dollar bailout money, next
scheduled to be delivered on September 25 in a tranche of about 1
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
He revealed the IMF and the Indonesian government were working
on a new letter of intent, expected to be completed by Friday,
which would outline the government's economic policies.
</P>
<P>
The other main element of the document would be the
restructuring of local corporations' domestic debts for the
resumption of commercial bank loans to restart production.
</P>
<P>
"I'm happy with the progress (of the reform program)," Neiss
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
