<HEADLINE> Malta's Nationalist Leader Back to Prime Minister's Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Eddie Fenech Adami, leader of
Malta's Nationalist Party, was sworn in as prime minister Sunday
night, only 22 months since he stepped down.
</P>
<P>
The Nationalist Party defeated the Labor Party led by the
previous prime minister, Alfred Sant, in the election held
Saturday by winning 51.7 percent of the votes and obtaining 35 of
the 69 seats in the parliament, said reports from Valletta,
capital of Malta.
</P>
<P>
About 95 percent of the 278,000 eligible voters turned out for
the election.
</P>
<P>
Adami would soon announce the list of cabinet members, said
officials of the prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that Adami's government will make a
priority of reviving Malta's bid for the European Union
membership, stalled by Sant, who held that Malta was not ready for
the sacrifices needed for EU eligibility.
</P>
<P>
Adami will also set about reducing the high utility rates,
which caused many complaints. The rates were imposed by Sant's
government to cut the deficit.
</P>
<P>
Adami, 64, had been Malta's prime minister for nine years until
his party was defeated by Sant's Labor Party in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
Internal divisions within the Labor Party forced Sant to risk
moving the election three years forward, in the hope that the
unfavorable situation in his party could be reversed.
</P>
<P>
Sant tendered his resignation to Malta's president after the
results of the election came out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
