<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Lawyer Wants Preview of Starr Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton's lawyers asked Monday that they be given an advance copy
of any report to Congress from Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr
on the president's affair with Monica Lewinsky so they could craft
a written reply to accompany the document.
</P>
<P>
David Kendall, the president's personal lawyer, made the
request in a letter to Starr, to ensure "elemental fairness" to
the president, Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
A final report by Starr on his investigation into Clinton's
relationship with Lewinsky, the former White House intern, and
possible obstruction of justice, perjury and abuse of power could
go to Congress as early as this month.
</P>
<P>
"Elemental fairness dictates that we be allowed to respond to
any `report' you send to the House simultaneously with its
transmission," Kendall wrote.
</P>
<P>
Kendall asked that the president's legal team as well as White
House lawyers be allowed to review a draft of Starr's report and
be given a week "to submit a written reply" that would be
submitted to the special appeals court panel overseeing the
special prosecutor, and then to Congress for possible impeachment
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
Kendall expressed concern that Starr's report might go beyond a
detail of facts gathered in the seven months of grand jury
investigation into the Lewinsky matter, and include "factual legal
analysis and conclusions" that would be unfair to the president
and contrary to the intent of Congress when it established the
office of independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
Kendall argued that Congress in requiring the independent
counsel to report to the House "was also sharply aware of the
potential abuse that the subjects of these reports might suffer...
(that) the power to damage reputations in the final report is
significant".
</P>
<P>
"We believe that fundamental fairness dictates that we have the
opportunity to review such a document and submit simultaneously
any reply we wish to make," Kendall wrote.
</P>
<P>
A copy of the letter was provided to Associated Press by
Kendall's office.
</P>
<P>
During the Reagan administration, the targets of the
Iran-Contra special prosecutor were allowed to review the
prosecutors' final report before it was released. Their dissenting
views were incorporated into the report released publicly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
