<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Objects to NLD Convening of Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government
reiterated its objection to the convening of a national parliament
by the country's National League for Democracy (NLD), according to
an official Information Sheet released here Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The NLD is reportedly to sponsor this month the parliament
elected in the 1990 multi-party general election, after its
ultimatum to the government for the move received no response.
</P>
<P>
The government warned that "if such an action is to be
implemented by an individual political party, it can lead to
institutional confusion and adversely affect national security."
</P>
<P>
The government had also warned earlier that "it would amount to
the NLD making herself a parallel government which no government
in the world would accept." It also threatened to take action when
it is left with no choice.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NLD charged in a statement Monday afternoon that
the Myanmar government has been arresting NLD members since last
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Up to Monday, a total of 110 NLD members including 50
parliament representatives-elect and 60 state, division and
township party organizers had been detained, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The NLD has repeatedly demanded the convening of the parliament
elected in the 1990 election in accordance with the then Election
Law and on June 23 set a deadline for the ruling State Peace and
Development Council to hold the parliament within 60 days.
</P>
<P>
After it received no response from the government on the expiry
of the deadline on August 21, the NLD declared its intention to
convene the parliament by itself in September.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990 election, participated by 93 political parties, the
NLD won 396 out of the 485 parliamentary seats.
</P>
<P>
The government began holding a National Convention in January
1993 for drafting a new state constitution.
</P>
<P>
However, all the delegates of the NLD's representatives-elect
withdrew from the convention in November 1995, four months after
Aung San Suu Kyi, the party's general secretary, was released from
nearly six years' house arrest.
</P>
<P>
The National Convention has been in recess for two and a half
years since the last session ended in March 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
