<HEADLINE> Champagne from Sunken Ship Up for Auction in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 7 (Xinhua)-- Twenty-four bottles of
champagne salvaged from the sunken ship Jonkoping will be
auctioned at the British auction house Christies in October,
according to Swedish News Agency TT.
</P>
<P>
Claes Bergvall, leader of a Swedish-Danish diving team that
recovered the treasure, said interest in the champagne has been
overwhelming and he expects the auction price to reach around
3,000 U.S. dollars a bottle.
</P>
<P>
The 2,400 bottles of champagne were recovered from the
Jonkoping that was sunk by a German submarine in 1916 on its way
from Gavle, Sweden to Rauma in Finland.
</P>
<P>
Bergvall said many internationally prominent figures have shown
great interest in the champagne.
</P>
<P>
Bergvall and his colleague Lindberg found the ship last year
off Finland's west coast.
</P>
<P>
The champagne had lain untouched for more than 80 years until
several bottles were recovered by the expedition a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The champagne is the same marque as that stocked aboard the
Titanic when it sank in 1912. 
</P>
</TEXT>
