<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Most American Workers Welcome Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A new study released
Monday shows that a great majority of American workers appreciate
employer-sponsored training and education.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by The Gallup Organization and commissioned by
three U.S. companies, said that, among 1012 employees interviewed, 80
percent said the availability of company-sponsored training programs
was a factor in deciding whether to accept a new job or stick with a
current one.
</P>
<P>
American workers, especially the yong workers called Generation
Xers, also view training as a way to improve their chances of getting
promoted.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show 58 percent of workers 32 years old or younger said
training was useful in preparing them for higher-level jobs.
Forty-two percent of workers older than that had the same opinion.
</P>
<P>
The United States spends something like 60 to 70 billion U.S.
dollars a year in workplace education and training, according to the
study which, however, adding that U.S. companies lag behind their
Japanese and European counterparts in terms of training dollars spent
per worker.
</P>
<P>
"Employees want more training than they are getting," said
Christine Sullivan, a spokeswoman for the three companies that
commissioned the Gallup survey.
</P>
<P>
Rich Wellins, senior vice president of Development Dimensions
International, one of the three companies, said that investing in
worker education can boost employee loyalty as well as corporate
profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
