<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expects Booming Development of Marine Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China is stepping up efforts
to exploit its huge marine resources in the future, which includes
exploring offshore oil and gas, developing seaside tourism and
ocean-related pharmaceuticals, and desalination sea water.
</P>
<P>
Such moves are needed to sustain the rapid economic growth of
the country, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
Major oil producers in China are striving to increase their oil
and natural gas output. The Bohai Oil Company, for example, plans
to increase its annual offshore oil output to six million tons by
2000 from the present 2.1 million tons.
</P>
<P>
China's offshore oil production reached 16 million tons last
year and natural gas reached four billion cubic meters. More than
six billion U.S. dollars of foreign investment and technology has
been used in China's offshore energy exploitation in the past 16
years, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
China is also advancing its oil exploration to deep-sea areas
because the government has realized that the majority of its oil
reserve is there.
</P>
<P>
In tourism, statistics show that seaside resort cities and
offshore islands in China are playing host to 10 million tourists
from inland provinces every summer. Since the early 1990s, the
income of the country's coastal tourist industry has been growing
30 percent every year. This is why many seaside cities are
competing to erect fancy hotels and sporting new golf courses.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that the sea is abundant with resources for
producing medicine to treat tumors, heart disease and many other
ailments. No exact estimate of potential profits is available on
this new industry, but some 40 major investors have invested
billions of yuan in this market and created one billion yuan of
earnings last year.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has listed desalination of sea water and
its direct use as priority projects because around 300 cities do
not have enough fresh water.
</P>
<P>
Sea-water processing bases in China are converting four million
tons of sea water to drinking water each year, and six billion
cubic meters of sea water are used in industrial production such
as cooling.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government also plans to import the latest
desalination systems to form the framework of a new industry
together with homemade machines developed during the past two
decades.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanxi Vows to Help Disabled People Shake off Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province
has vowed to help all of its handicapped people shake off poverty
by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
The province now has 1.34 million handicapped people, and
458,000 of them live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
To reach its goal, the province has done a great deal to
create employment opportunities for the disabled, and to provide
rehabilitation, education, training and other services.
</P>
<P>
All of the province's 119 counties, cities and townships and
neighborhoods have established federations for the disabled to
promote these programs, according to provincial officials.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi is the first province in China to provide scholarships
for the handicapped, and some percent of the handicapped children
of school age are now attending school, compared to 60 percent
before 1993.
</P>
<P>
The province has offered 890 training courses for 53,000
disabled over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
In the province's cities and towns, 79 percent of the disabled
who are capable of working have found jobs. Eleven of the
province's prefectures and cities, and more than 70 counties, have
established poverty-relief funds for the disabled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
