<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Ex-President to Run for OAS Secretary-General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Former Costa Rican President
Rafael Angel Calderon has begun consultations with some of the
Latin American countries on his possibility of becoming the
secretary general of the Organization of the American States (OAS).
</P>
<P>
Calderon will compete with incumbent OAS Secretary-General
Cesar Gaviria, who has expressed his desire to take a second term
of the position. The elections will be held in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
As Gaviria has been in the position for five years, the
opportunity should be given to a Central American country, the
newspaper "La Nacion" quoted Calderon as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gaviria, former Colombian president, defeated former Costa
Rican Foreign Minister Bernd Niehaus in 1994 to become the OAS
chief.
</P>
<P>
The OAS, founded in 1948, aims to foster peace, security,
mutual understanding and cooperation among the nations of the
Western Hemisphere. The organization is made up of 35 countries
from the American continent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
