Chinese Minister of Finance Xiang Huaicheng. They are also
scheduled to tour Shanghai apart from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- China aims to reduce the rate of leprosy to less than 0.1
per 10,000 in 95 percent of counties and cities by 2000 and reach
that standard in all the counties and cities by 2010, according to
an official from the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Yin Dakui, vice-minister of health, told the 15th International
Leprosy Congress which opened yesterday, that more than 490,000
leprosy patients had been detected in China from 1949 to 1997,
and 4,045 patients need treatment at present.
</P>
<P>
-- Navigation on the Yangtze River, which had been blocked by
floods for 43 days, fully resumed yesterday.
</P>
<P>
On July 26, the Chinese government issued an order to ban
navigation on the river in an effort to ensure the security of the
dikes.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Remarkable results have been achieved since border police
stepped up anti-smuggling efforts in mid-July, public security
sources said yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
-- Four top universities in east China's Zhejiang Province will
merge next week to become China's largest university.
</P>
<P>
-- The Ministry of Justice has finished sounding out the
businesses run by the country's judicial bodies. 
</P>
