<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Lowers Forecast for Export Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Swedish Trade Council
has downgraded its forecast for the growth of exports this year
from six to five percent.
</P>
<P>
The forecast for next year's exports has been revised lower to
between four to five percent, Swedish news agency TT reported.
</P>
<P>
"The market outlook is worse in several parts of the world,"
said the trade council's chief economist Mauro Gozzo.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian crisis has lingered ... and we clearly see further
turmoil in Japan, South Korea, and the countries where the crisis
began, such as Thailand, Malaysia and Indonesia," Gozzo said.
</P>
<P>
"We also see a worse outlook in our neighbor Norway which would
weigh heavily on Swedish exports," he said.
</P>
<P>
The previous official forecast of 3.1 percent growth in the
Swedish economy for 1999 was "too optimistic", Gozzo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
