<HEADLINE> Graf Wants to Take a Rest After Beaten in U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Five-times U.S. Open champion
Steffi Graf of Germany is feeling upset after losing her match
yesterday and wants to take a rest after the U.S. Open tennis
championships.
</P>
<P>
The veteran said here today: "I'm taking a little break after
this tournament. I've played a lot in the past few weeks. I'll
probably play a couple of tournaments in Europe."
</P>
<P>
Graf, eighth seed at the Open, was eliminated by Patty Schnyder
of Switzerland last night in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
"I'm taking a rest for now. When I started playing my first
tournaments in England, I had no expectations whatsoever. Really,
it
hasn't changed very much. I've really been going into the
tournaments with no expectations whatsoever. At times it has been
difficult to accept that it is going to take a certain time. There
were good and bad moments, but in general I've been pretty happy
the
way it's been going."
</P>
<P>
Graf missed last year's Open due to knee surgery which had
tamed
her more than one year. She only won one title this season and
currently ranks outside of the top 20 in the world.
</P>
<P>
Schnyder said: "It's hard to tell if her backhand is vulnerable
now because I didn't play against her wen she won all those
tournaments. I just think there is such a lot of respect towards
her. But I think fear is not the right word." 
</P>
</TEXT>
