<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 01:00 GMT, September 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Air Canada and its striking pilots have agreed to
resume talks in Montreal Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The strike by 2,100 pilots of the airline is in its sixth day.
It was called after talks broke off over wages and working
conditions. (Air Canada-Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece reiterated Monday that it still opposed the
ban to be imposed by European Union (EU) on flights by Yugoslav
carriers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a working talks here with visiting Bosnian Serb
Prime Minister Milorad Dodid, Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos said that Athens was still against the EU flight ban
decision which was made two months ago because the present
situation in Kosovo was different, and Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic had expressed willingness to begin peace talks with the
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. (Greece-EU Ban-Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Twenty-one German soldiers were injured, five of them
seriously, when a hand grenade exploded during a routine training
at their barracks Monday, the German Defense Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred Monday morning in a classroom of the
German troops based in the southern German town of Amberg.
</P>
<P>
German authorities said that they had launched an investigation
about possible violation of safety rules by an army
officer. (Germany-Explosion)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Peace talks aimed at ending the civil war in
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) was over in Victoria Falls,
Zimbabwe later Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the summit, Zambian President Frederick Chiluba,
announced that an agreement would be signed at 9 a.m. (0700 GMT)
Tuesday morning, South African national TV (SABC)
reported. (S.Africa-Congo Peace Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- NASA researchers said they had captured images of
Hurricane Bonnie's "sky-scraping" cloud using the first space-bone
rain radar, orbiting aboard the U.S.-Japanese spacecraft Tropical
Rainfall Measuring Mission.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from Monday's Washington Post, the cloud
rose 59000 feet into the sky out of the Hurricane's central eye
wall. This is the first time that the radar has seen a structure
of this type in a hurricane approaching the U.S. East
Coast. (US-Hurricane-Bonnie)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British government Monday dismissed Libyan
complaints about plans to try the two Libyans accused of
undertaking the Lockerbie bombing, saying there was no agreement
of extraditing the two Libyans if they were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi said Saturday that the
Anglo-American proposal of undertaking the trial in The Hague was
a ploy and that the two Libyans could be extradited to Britain
once the trial was over.
</P>
<P>
A British Foreign Office spokesman said early Monday that the
joint proposal specifically ruled out any kind of extradition
after the trial and guaranteed the two men would be returned to
Libya if they were acquitted. (UK-Lockerbie-Libya)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The world has been mercifully free from
large-scale regional conflict over the past year, but many local
wars have continued with new ones breaking out, said
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his annual report 1998 on peace and Security, Annan said
there had been some important successes for the international
community, including the restoration of the democratically elected
Government in Sierra Leone. (Annan-Report-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
here Monday that the Israeli-Turkish cooperation would improve
the prosperity and security of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting with his Turkish
counterpart Mesut Yilmaz, Netanyahu said that he discussed with
Yilmaz the economic, political and defense relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed that Israeli cooperation with Turkey was the
"natural cooperation" that is "not against anyone" and will
contribute to the stability of the
region. (Israel-Turkey-Cooperation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Forty-nine percent of Russia's urban residents have
no money to soften the impact of the financial crisis, according
to a recent poll earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen percent of the respondents were buying extra supplies
of foodstuffs, 5 percent were stocking up on consumer goods, 4
percent were buying durables and another 4 percent were buying
U.S. dollars, the poll shows.
</P>
<P>
The poll was organized by the All-Russia Public Opinion Center
and involved 1,862 Russian residents in
September. (Russia-Crisis-Poll) 
</P>
