<HEADLINE> Martinez Troubled by Injury in U.S. Open Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Amanda Coetzer of South
Africa
outlasted seventh seed Conchita Martinez of Spain to enter the
quarterfinals of the U.S. Open tennis championships here this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The 13th seed Coetzer beat Martinez 6-4, 4-6, 6-2 in a
two-hour,
38-minute marathon. It was the first time for Coetzer to beat
Martinez, who had won all 12 meetings over Coetzer before.
</P>
<P>
"She's been a very tough opponent for me my whole career," said
Coetzer. "It's great, especially because it's at a Grand Slam. I
think I just never felt like I really went out with a good game
plan
against her. I was getting a little confused and frustrated. I
think
today I set out to not get frustrated, just go out with a specific
game plan and stick with it."
</P>
<P>
The match witnessed both players lofted moonballs from the
baseline and the winner turned out as the one who made less
errors.
After Coetzer won the first set, the conservative play
intensified.
</P>
<P>
The second game of the second set consumed 29 minutes and
consisted of 11 deuces. Martinez finally broke Coetzer on her
fifth
break point and went on to take the set.
</P>
<P>
But Martinez, playing with a severe sprain, had little left in
the third rubber and Coetzer put away the match to earn her third
U.S. Open quarterfinal berth.
</P>
<P>
Martinez said: "It was difficult for me to play my own game
because I was injured. Basically, I'd say I was about 60 percent
of
my abilities today. When you're like that against a player like
Amanda that doesn't give up, it's difficult. I had pain when I was
playing the high balls. You cannot turn. I thought of retiring in
the first set but I decided to hang in there. At least I fought. I
gave it a shot. That's all I could have done." 
</P>
</TEXT>
