<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, IMF Agree on GNP Growth for 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) and the Philippine government have agreed to aim for a
4.1-percent gross national product (GNP) growth rate in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two sides planned a 3.5-percent growth for the
country's gross domestic product (GDP) next year during a two-week
review of the Philippine economy by an IMF panel, Business World
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The targets paint the Philippines as one of the few economies
in East Asia that will see an expansion next year.
</P>
<P>
Four Asian countries, namely Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia and
South Korea, are all expected to experience a recession next year,
according to economists.
</P>
<P>
Central bank governor Gabriel Singson said the Philippines'
inflation is expected to slow down to 8.5 percent in 1999 from the
10-percent level expected by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the El Nino-induced drought and the effects of the
Asian financial crisis will be sidelined next year as the economy
starts its slow walk toward recovery.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the IMF and Manila also agreed to cut the Philippines'
GNP target for 1998 to 1.5 percent from the original 2-3 percent
and the GDP to 1 percent from the earlier planned 1.5-2.5percent.
</P>
<P>
The multinational institution also allowed the country to have
a 40-billion-peso (930 million U.S. dollars) budget deficit this
year, instead of a planned surplus of 5 billion pesos (116 million
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
