<HEADLINE> Football Shares Soar in Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Confirmation that BSkyB is in
talks to take over English premier league soccer club Manchester
United made all football sector shares soar in London Stock
Market on Monday.
</P>
<P>
After Manchester United confirmed takeover talks, shares leapt
by 30% to close at 206.5p from a closing price of 159p on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Now there is mounting speculation in the City that a bidding
frenzy could engulf the football sector.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that rival media groups, desperate to compete
with BSkyB, will rush to buy some of the Premiership's other top
clubs.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United's Premiership rivals led the share price
charge, with values rising across the board when the stock market
opened.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Chelsea closed more than 9% up at 78p; in Aston
Villa,the shares rose more than 9% to 615p; in Leeds Sporting,
parent company of Leeds United, almost 10% to 14p; in Tottenham
Hotspur,5.6% to 64p and in Newcastle United, 8% to 67.5p.
</P>
<P>
The rise in share prices will bring a windfall to the hundreds
of thousands of fans who own a part of their favorite clubs.
</P>
<P>
Fans who bought shares in Manchester United shares when the
club floated seven years ago have seen the value of their
investment multiply more than sixteen times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
