<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crises in Asia, Russia Dampen World Business Climate: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The world business climate has cooled
down considerably due to the financial crises in Asia and Russia, an
economic survey conducted by a German economic institute said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts questioned by the German Ifo institute in 67
countries in July were much less optimistic in their economic
predictions for the next six months than they were three months ago,
the Ifo survey showed.
</P>
<P>
The business climate in Asia, where financial turmoil started more
than a year ago, had further deteriorated, with economic experts
seeing almost no chance for Japan to stop recession within this year,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
While predicting more crisis-related impact on many other Asian
economies, the Ifo survey also found rising fears that the Asian
crisis could spill over to Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile experts also saw the possibility of an economic slowdown
in the United States, Ifo said.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, the business climate in Western Europe continued to be
quite positive with the twin crises in Asia and Russia expected to
have only limited impact on the region.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, experts still predicted economic slowdown in parts of
Western Europe, especially in Britain, in the second half of this
year, Ifo said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
