<HEADLINE> Greece Still Opposes EU Flight Ban on Yugoslav Carriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Greece reiterated Monday that
it still opposed the ban to be imposed by European Union (EU) on
flights by Yugoslav carriers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a working talks here with visiting Bosnian Serb
Prime Minister Milorad Dodid, Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos said that Athens was still against the EU flight ban
decision which was made two months ago because the present
situation in Kosovo was different, and Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic had expressed willingness to begin peace talks with the
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Milosevic had accepted the international
community's condition of wider autonomy for Kosovo, although the
Albanian community continued to seek independence, which was
unacceptable to the international community.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Dodik said that the EU decision to ban Yugoslav
carriers flights was the worst and did not help a resolution of
problems in Yugoslavia or Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Both men agreed that there had to be an end to hostilities as
soon as possible and it was the right of each state to defend its
territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
As for the scheduled general elections in Bosnia, Dodik said
that it would provide the Bosnian Serb Republic with the
wherewithal to implement the 1995 Dayton peace accords. 
</P>
