<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Reaffirms Commitment to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian military leader
General Abdulsalam Abubakar has reaffirmed his government's
commitment to hand over an elected civilian government by May
next year.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement issued at the at a press conference in
the capital city Monday, he said: "The officer and men of the
Nigerian armed forces and police, like the generality of our
people yearn for democracy in a united and peaceful country."
</P>
<P>
While Abubaka has seemingly won the trust of many people about
his sincerity, still some doubt that the military forces might
want to stick to power, which they have managed to do in most of
the time since Nigeria won independence in 1960.
</P>
<P>
Asked under what circumstances he or the military might think
it is necessary to take over again, Abubakar said he hoped it
will never happen.
</P>
<P>
Repeating his appeal to the country's exiles abroad to return
and join the so-called all inclusive democratic process, Abubakar
disclosed that he has given instructions to the Ministry of
Justice to withdraw charges against them.
</P>
<P>
When asked if he thinks his administration has done enough to
satisfy the international community's demand to democratize
Nigeria, Abubakar said democratization is the need of Nigeria
itself and its success should not be measured by the satisfaction
of the international society.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Abubakar reaffirmed his
administration's transpancy to sustaining the independence of
and transparency of the new independence electoral committee,
which he inauguarated on August 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
