<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Canada to Stop Gas Flaring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and Canada are expected
to seal a comprehensive blueprint to put out the flaring of
associated gas at Nigeria's oil wells at a follow-up forum to be
held in Abuja later this month.
</P>
<P>
Representatives attending the forum will discuss emission
reduction strategies including the clean development mechanism,
the clean air strategic alliance, and the voluntary challenge and
register program, according to local press reports.
</P>
<P>
The gas flaring which has lasted for the past 40 years in the
West African country would be virtually eradicated in the next 10
years.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting held last June in Canada between the
National Committee of the Nigerian Vision and the Canadian
Petroleum, the blueprint is to be tabled at the scheduled forum
for endorsement.
</P>
<P>
"Nigeria recognizes the need to make a major effort to reduce
greenhouse gas emissions by eliminating the flaring of gases,"
a senior Nigerian official said.
</P>
<P>
The Abuja forum will explore innovations already developed by
Canadian oil industry operatives concerning industry-wide
initiatives targeted at encouraging corporate commitment to
flaring reduction strategies, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian oil fields produce up to two billion standard cubic
feet of natural gas daily as by-products of oil exploration, out
of which about 90 percent is routinely flared at flow stations.
</P>
<P>
With natural gas resources estimated at 3,500 billion cubic
feet, Nigeria is rated as having the 10th largest reserves of
natural gas in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has recently introduced a series of
generous incentives for the use of natural gas in the country and
also invested billions of Dollars in the Nigeria Liquefied
Natural Gas Ltd. in order to produce more liquefied gas for
export.
</P>
<P>
All the major oil companies operating in the country have
embarked on projects to use gas associated with oil production
with the biggest project under construction at a cost of 3.8
billion U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
