<HEADLINE> Most Disabled Ugandan Children From Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Most children with
disabilities in Uganda are from very poor families which cannot
afford nursery school fees, a health official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kirsten Kristensen, a coordinator in the Ministry of Health,
made the remarks when opening a five-day workshop near Kampala
for nursery school and infant teachers on early intervention on
children especially those with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
A Radio Uganda report quoted the coordinator as saying that
many schoo do not admit children with disabilities because
they fear that these children may lower the standards of schools.
</P>
<P>
Veronica Mpagi, a consultant on early intervention, said
nursery teachers play a crucial role in the development of a
child and the child's education.
</P>
<P>
With more children with special needs than ever before, she
added, nursery teachers as basic educators should know what is
needed for the early intervention in a child's development and
they are urged to pay more attention and care to children with
visually and hearing problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
