<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Gets Anti-AIDS Award From WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has been awarded the
World Health Organization's (WHO) 50th anniversary award for its
excellent AIDS prevention work.
</P>
<P>
Gro Harlem Brundtland, the WHO's new director-general,
presented the award in Harare during the 48th session of the
regional committee for Africa, Radio Uganda reported Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
WHO's regional director Ebrahim Samba said that HIV prevalence
in Uganda has declined from 30 percent in 1989 to 15 percent in
1997 among mothers attending antenatal clinics and public
awareness has reached 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
He praised Uganda's impressive campaign as the first success
story in the fight against AIDS in Africa and therefore it is the
beacon of hope for the continent which has been widely affected
by the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
In accepting the award, Ugandan Minister of State for Health
Philip Byaruhanga attributed the success to the highest political
commitment by President Yoweri Museveni who initiated a
multi-sectoral AIDS control program.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed the role of extensive health education
combined with community mobilization, including civic, political
and religious leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
