<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, September 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- About 300,000 Israeli public workers ended a
general strike Sunday after the main labor federation reached an
agreement over pay raises with the treasury in the morning, Israel
Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that representatives from both the Histadrut,
Israel's labor federation, and the Finance Ministry expressed
satisfactions over the agreement, the details of which were not
disclosed. (Israel-Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
here Monday that the Israeli-Turkish cooperation would improve the
prosperity and security of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting with his Turkish
counterpart Mesut Yilmaz, Netanyahu said that he discussed with
Yilmaz the economic, political and defense relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed that Israeli cooperation with Turkey was the
"natural cooperation" that is "not against anyone" and will
contribute to the stability of the region.
(Israel-Turkey-Cooperation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Saudi Arabian King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz Monday
urged Iran and Afghan Taliban militia to exercise restraint and
resolve their disputes peacefully, the Kuwait News Agency (Kuna)
reported from Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd issued his call at the Cabinet session he chaired for
the first time after recuperation from his recent illness.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran and Taliban should start "a constructive
dialogue that embodies the spirit of Islamic brotherhood and
sincere intents..."
</P>
<P>
Fahd's statement came amid rising tension between Iran and
Taliban after Tehran accused the Taliban militia of kidnapping 10
Iranian diplomats when they took over the northern city of Mazari
Sharif on August 8. (Saudi-Iran-Afghanistan Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The International Rice Commission (IRC) convened here
Monday to mainly explore ways to meet the challenges to
sustainable rice production.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session of the IRC, which is under the Food and
Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), FAO's
Director-General Jacques Diouf said the three-day meeting was held
at a time when 800 million people around the world are still
suffering mal-nutrition and the demand for rice is on rise.
</P>
<P>
Diouf said the immediate task for the 61 IRC member states,
world major rice producers, is to identify ways of raising
production while conserving the natural resource bases for future
generation. (Egypt-Rice-FAO) 
</P>
</TEXT>
