<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Declares War on Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA (Nigeria), September 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian military
leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar has declared war on corruption
in the country that has been dubbed as one of the most corrupt
nation in the world by some sectors of the world community.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in the capital Monday, Abubakar
said his administration is committeed to instilling transparency,
accountability and probity in public life.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the government has started investigations
into the conduct of certain government departments in the
disbursement and application of public funds.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that routine audit and investigations of various
accounts in the office of the National Security Adviser and other
government departments and agencies are ongoing.
</P>
<P>
The former national security adviser to the late head of
state, General Sani Abacha, has been accused of stealing tens of
thousands of U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The investigations are aimed to recover advancement payment
for contracts that have not been executed or whose prices were
over inflated and monies that were not properly used.
</P>
<P>
Noting that these investigations are not formal administrative
or judicial inquiries, he said they have achieved appreciable
results.
</P>
<P>
"All those that have been questioned have co-operated and
voluntarily refunded some money, which are being kept in a
special account in the Central Bank of Nigeria," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar also announced the re-organization of the Ministry of
Petroleum Resources and the Nigerian National Petroleum
Corporation (NNPC), which he said is central to the
revitalization of the Nigerian economy.
</P>
<P>
The two above-mentioned bodies have been widely accused of
mismanaging Nigeria's huge income from oil exporting, which
amounts to more than 10 billion U.S. Dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
During his recent reshuffle of the cabinet which he inherited
from late head of state, General Sani Abacha, Abubakar did not
appoint a new petroleum minister.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he appointed a special adviser to help him supervise
the ministry directly.
</P>
<P>
For the future, Abubakar said he will create an independent
commission to regulate and monitor the petroleum sector.
</P>
<P>
A special adviser on energy will be appointed to coordinate
the activities of the NNPC and the independent commission, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
