<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Refutes Libyan Complaints Over Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The British government Monday
dismissed Libyan complaints about plans to try the two Libyans
accused of undertaking the Lockerbie bombing, saying there was no
agreement of extraditing the two Libyans if they were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi said Saturday that the
Anglo-American proposal of undertaking the trial in The Hague was
a ploy and that the two Libyans could be extradited to Britain
once the trial was over.
</P>
<P>
A British Foreign Office spokesman said early Monday that the
joint proposal specifically ruled out any kind of extradition
after the trial and guaranteed the two men would be returned to
Libya if they were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
"There has never been any suggestion of a transit point.
Gaddafi is building on a word which doesn't have any relevance.
Gaddafi is either not reading the small print or he is
prevaricating," he said.
</P>
<P>
"After being moved to the Netherlands the two men would be
extradited from Dutch jurisdiction to Scottish jurisdiction in the
form of the Scottish court in The Hague. That's all," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that Britain was ready to give
assurances about the plan but made clear this had to be done
through the offices of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Some 270 people were killed when a Pan AM airliner exploded
over the Scottish town of Lockerbie on December 21, 1988 and the
U.N. imposed strict international sanctions on Libya in 1992 after
the Libyan government refused to hand over the alleged bombers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
