<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Stage Strong Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- An across-the-board rally in
Asia on hints from U.S. Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan
that U.S. rates could be cut spread to European bourses, which
staged a general rally on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The London Footsie finished strongly holding onto big gains
after Alan Greenspan's hints that he is prepared to lower interest
rates if necessary. The FTSE 100 index finished just off the day's
highs, up 180 at 5347.
</P>
<P>
In a speech on Friday, Greenspan said that the Fed had shifted
away from its tightening bias on interest rates. His pessimistic
assessment about the likely impact of Asian and Russian turmoil on
the U.S. economy also suggested that he was beginning to favor a
U.S. rate cut.
</P>
<P>
The bullish mood infected Asian markets and most of the
continent and paved the way for a big rally on the footsie.
</P>
<P>
Sentiment was further lifted by talk that UK rates had peaked
and would head down in the near future.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German stocks joined the global rebound but the
dollar's decline and a second prime ministerial vote in Russia
tempered gains.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax index closed at 4945, up 81 points with key
stocks slipping in late trade from large gains seen earlier in the
day.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks benefited most from early trading activity, as
fears over their exposure to Russia dissipated once again. Merck
Finck &AMP; Co.'s Eckhard Frahm said "The market is slowly beginning
to understand the message" that the Russian crisis isn't a major
concern for German banks.
</P>
<P>
Traders said comments by Alan Greenspan Friday hinting at a
potential interest rate cut gave trading a boost, even though U.S.
markets are closed due to a public holiday, although Labor Day
also ensured that Frankfurt trade was thin.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French stocks moved ahead with other European markets
although trade was disturbed by technical problems in the
afternoon. The leading Cac-40 index 3795 closed up 104 points.
</P>
<P>
Traders said market players are still very concerned about
political developments in Russia and are trying to evaluate which
kind of stocks are safest before making any moves.
</P>
<P>
"Investors are asking questions to figure out the sensitivity
of various business sectors," said Richard Morisseau, a salesman
at brokerage house Meeschaert Rousselle.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
