<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Recognizes UNITA's Renovation Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Brazil became the first
country to recognize the newly formed party, broken away from
Angolan opposition UNITA, to help solve the peace crisis in the
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA Renovation Committee was set up after some members
of the opposition, National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) broke up with UNITA Chairman Jonas Savimbi on
September 3.
</P>
<P>
Addor Neto, Brazil's Ambassador to Angola, said here Monday on
the occasi marking the 176th anniversary of Brazilian
Independence that his government is in favor of the principle of
the renovation committee of giving up war for the peace of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Neto said that the UNITA headed by Jonas Savimbi is not
interested in the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol, as Savimbi's UNITA
group has cut off its cooperation with peace observer nations and
failed to observe its obligations outlined in the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian ambassador said that the UN Special Envoy to
Angola, Issa Diallo, should grip the opportunity for peace in the
country as the new UNITA group has a good will for peace.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has announced to sever its relations
with Savimbi's UNITA and asked the international community to
recognize the UNITA Renovation Committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
