<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lagos Bus Drivers on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Commercial vehicle
operators Monday went on strike in Lagos, paralyzing the city all
the day.
</P>
<P>
The striking drivers carrying placards and chanting songs
embarked on a peaceful protest against the recognition by the
Lagos government of officials of the National Union of Road
Transport (NURTW) and Road Transport Employers Association
(RTEAN).
</P>
<P>
The drivers are protesting against the return of the NURTW and
RTEAN officials who, they alleged, have been extorting drivers at
the motor parks, the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reported.
</P>
<P>
They stormed the Victoria Island office of the Nigerian
Television Authority (NTA) in five over-loaded buses and then
went to the office of the Lagos state military administrator to
formally register their grievances.
</P>
<P>
In a nine-point resolution contained in their public notice,
the striking drivers called for the "total disengagement of NURTW
and RTEAN from all motor parks".
</P>
<P>
The notice advised all vehicle owners to keep their vehicles
within their domain until the vexed issues were settled.
</P>
<P>
"All sectors of commercial drivers should cease work as from
Monday, September 7, until further notice," it said.
</P>
<P>
As there were no commercial buses in Lagos Monday, many
commuters had to walk to their destinations and most offices were
empty.
</P>
<P>
The striking drivers belong to five associations including
Lagos State Taxi Drivers' Association and Urban Commercial Bus
Drivers' Association of Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Capture Bonnie's Cloud Images </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- NASA researchers said
they had captured images of Hurricane Bonnie's "sky-scraping"
cloud using the first space-bone rain radar, orbiting aboard the
U.S.-Japanese spacecraft Tropical Rainfall Measuring Mission.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from Monday's Washington Post, the
cloud rose 59000 feet into the sky out of the Hurricane's
central eye wall. This is the first time that the radar has seen
a structure of this type in a hurricane approaching the U.S.
East Coast.
</P>
<P>
Many scientists believe that the vast amount of warm, moist
air carried aloft in such a tower, and the subsequent release of
latent energy in the form of rain, is the precursor for an
intensification of the hurricane. That was what happened to
Bonnie a day or two later, they said.
</P>
<P>
They said the cloud probably formed because Bonnie was moving
very slowly. The lack of movement kept funneling warm moist air
into the upper atmosphere, thus raising the entire height of the
tropopause which is normally around 45000 feet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980908.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Prime Minister Rejects Union Calls for Economic Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair rejected demands for a change in government economic policy
during a meeting with union leaders in Downing Street Monday.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that any relaxation in the tough policy would risk
destroying the major strides already made towards building a
stable economy.
</P>
<P>
Blair said that he understands the difficulties manufacturing
industry is facing as a result of high interest rates and the
strong pound. What business fears most is "a return to boom and
bust and 15 percent interest rates" which led to company failures
and job losses under the previous government, he added.
</P>
<P>
Labor's policy has been taken to get inflation under control
and in the long term interests of the economy, not for short term
political considerations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came after a week in which 600 workers at the
Fujitsu plant in Tony Blair's own Sedgefield constituency became
the latest casualties of the slump in the world market.
</P>
<P>
But critics are blaming the government's economic policy, high
interest rates and the level of the pound for domestic
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
As the economic situation abroad worsens and its effects
continue to be felt in Britain, trade union leaders urged Blair to
set up a special task force to stop the manufacturing industry
"sliding into recession."
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the meeting, Ken Jackson, general secretary of
the Amalgamated Engineering and Electrical Union, said an
immediate cut in interest rates is needed to avert massive new job
losses.
</P>
<P>
"Our message to the prime minister will be quite simple, that
there are something like 250,000 jobs at risk out there if
immediate action isn't taken," he said.
</P>
<P>
And senior Labor MP Martin O'Neill, chairman of the Commons'
trade and industry committee, also called on ministers to show a
"greater awareness of the concerns of business."
</P>
<P>
"At the present moment there is a sense that responsibility for
interest rates has been passed to the Bank of England Committee,
and at the same time there is not an appreciation by government of
what is happening in manufacturing industry," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
