<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Government Insists Lamb Is Safe to Eat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The British government is
advising the public Monday that lamb is safe to eat amid claims by
experts that the mad cow disease may have spread to sheep.
</P>
<P>
There was no "no evidence" to justify a ban on lamb sales, the
Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
But it said investigations into any possible risk to human
health would continue.
</P>
<P>
National anxiety was generated after a senior government
adviser on mad cow disease revealed that it is possible sheep may
have been infected with Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy(BSE), the
so-called mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
Professor Jeffrey Almond, head of the sheep subcommittee of the
government BSE watchdog SEAC (the spongiform encephalopathy
advisory committee), told a radio program that there is "distinct
possibility that BSE is out there in the sheep population."
</P>
<P>
The problem had been known about since 1996, Almond said Monday
in BBC radio's early morning program Farming Today. He warned that
if the BSE is found in the sheep, it would be a national
emergency.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of BSE in Britain has been linked to the use of
cattle feed that included the remains of sheep infected with
scrapie, a form of BSE.
</P>
<P>
But humans are not thought to be at risk from the conventional
form of scrapie that has infected sheep for centuries.
</P>
<P>
If firm evidence is produced that BSE can pass to sheep, it
could lead to the mass destruction of the 42 million-strong flock
in Britain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
